{"title_page": "Slovenian Democratic Party", "text_new": "{{Infobox political party\n| name = Slovenian Democratic Party\n| native_name = Slovenska demokratska stranka\n| logo = SDS logotype.svg\n| colorcode = {{Slovenian Democratic Party/meta/color}}\n| leader = [[Janez Jan\u0161a]]\n| foundation = 16 February 1989\n| headquarters = [[Ljubljana]]\n| ideology = [[Slovenian nationalism]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/jun/03/anti-immigration-party-leads-exit-poll-in-slovenian-election|title=Slovenian nationalist party set for power after winning election|last=Agencies|date=4 June 2018|website=the Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-06-03/ally-of-eu-s-orban-wins-inconclusive-slovenian-vote-poll-shows|title=Another Euro Member Heads for Turmoil After Nationalist Win|date=3 June 2018|publisher=|via=www.bloomberg.com}}</ref><br />[[National conservatism]]<ref>{{cite web|website=Parties and Elections in Europe|title=Slovenia|last=Nordsieck|first=Wolfram|year=2018|url=http://www.parties-and-elections.eu/slovenia.html|accessdate=20 March 2019}}</ref><br />[[Social conservatism]]<ref>https://www.reuters.com/article/us-slovenia-rights/slovenia-rejects-same-sex-marriages-in-a-referendum-idUSKBN0U30BS20151220</ref><br />[[Right-wing populism]]<ref name=\"euronews.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.euronews.com/2018/06/01/explained-slovenia-s-elections-and-orban-s-populist-influence|title=Explained: Slovenia's election and Orban's populist influence|date=1 June 2018|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/jun/01/drain-the-swamp-rightwing-leader-pulls-ahead-in-slovenias-polls|title='Drain the swamp': rightwing leader pulls ahead in Slovenia's polls|first=Andrew|last=MacDowall|date=1 June 2018|website=the Guardian}}</ref><ref name=\"nytimes.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2018/06/01/world/europe/ap-eu-slovenia-election.html|title=Anti-Immigrant Party Set to Make Gains in Slovenia Vote|date=1 June 2018|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref><br />[[Anti-immigration]]<ref name=\":7\"/><ref name=\"nytimes.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-slovenia-election/anti-immigrant-stance-helps-slovenias-sds-party-to-poll-lead-idUSKCN1IN1QU|title=Anti-immigrant stance helps Slovenia's SDS party to poll lead|first=Marja|last=Novak|publisher=}}</ref>{{sfn|Bakke|2010|p=244}}\n| position = '''Historical:'''<br />[[Centre-left politics|Centre-left]] (initially)<ref name=\"demsoc.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.demsoc.org/2014/05/19/slovenian-democratic-party-sds/|title=Slovenian Democratic Party (SDS) - The Democratic Society|website=www.demsoc.org}}</ref><ref name=\"Makarovi\u010dTom\u0161i\u010d\">{{cite book|author1=Matej Makarovi\u010d|author2=Matev\u017e Tom\u0161i\u010d|chapter=\u2018Left\u2018 and \u2019Right\u2019 in Slovenian Political Life and Public Discourse|editor=Constantine Arvanitopoulos|title=Reforming Europe: The Role of the Centre-Right|publisher=Springer|year=2009|page=264 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=G6gWLW2oDJ0C&pg=PA263}}</ref><br />[[Centre-right politics|Centre-right]]<ref name=\"demsoc.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.demsoc.org/2014/05/19/slovenian-democratic-party-sds/|title=Slovenian Democratic Party (SDS) - The Democratic Society|website=www.demsoc.org}}</ref>{{sfn|Bakke|2010|p=244}}<ref name=\"Fink-Hafner2006\">{{cite book|author=Danica Fink-Hafner|chapter=Slovenia: Between Bipolarity and Broad Coalition-Building|editor=Susanne Jungerstam-Mulders|title=Post-communist EU Member States: Parties and Party Systems|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iNa6l58HNWoC&pg=PA218|year=2006|publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.|isbn=978-0-7546-4712-6|page=218}}</ref><ref name=\"Makarovi\u010dTom\u0161i\u010d\">{{cite book|author1=Matej Makarovi\u010d|author2=Matev\u017e Tom\u0161i\u010d|chapter=\u2018Left\u2018 and \u2019Right\u2019 in Slovenian Political Life and Public Discourse|editor=Constantine Arvanitopoulos|title=Reforming Europe: The Role of the Centre-Right|publisher=Springer|year=2009|page=264 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=G6gWLW2oDJ0C&pg=PA263}}</ref><ref name=\":57\"/><br />'''Contemporary:'''<br />[[Right-wing politics|Right-wing]]<ref name=\"HlousekKopecek\">{{Citation |first1=V\u00edt |last1=Hlou\u0161ek |first2=Lubom\u00edr |last2=Kope\u010dek |title=Origin, Ideology and Transformation of Political Parties: East-Central and Western Europe Compared |publisher=Ashgate |year=2010 |page=26 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=K79sdX-amEgC&pg=PA26|isbn=9780754678403 }}</ref><ref>{{Citation |first=Paul G. |last=Lewis |title=Political Parties in Post-Communist Eastern Europe |publisher=Routledge |year=2000 |page=167 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LAdhbhFzaYsC&pg=PA167|isbn=9780415201810 }}</ref><ref name=\"nytimes.com\"/><ref name=\":7\"/><ref name=\"euronews.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/anti-immigrant-party-set-make-gains-slovenia-vote-55584494|title=Anti-immigrant party set to make gains in Slovenia vote|first=ABC|last=News|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dw.com/en/orban-ally-janez-jansa-expected-to-top-slovenias-election/a-44055791|title=Orban ally Janez Jansa expected to top Slovenia's election - DW - 02.06.2018|first=Deutsche Welle|last=(www.dw.com)|website=DW.COM}}</ref><ref>http://www.total-slovenia-news.com/politics/1045-elections-2018-party-profiles-sds-the-janez-jansa-party-feature</ref><ref name=\":57\"/>\n| predecessor = [[Yugoslav Social-Democratic Party]] (not legal)\n| membership_year = 2013\n| membership = 30,000<ref>{{cite web|title=Planet Siol: SDS je z 30.000 \u010dlani gromozanska stranka proti ostalim. Virantovcev je le za \"jurja\".|url=http://www.politikis.si/?p=90370|website=Politikis|accessdate=30 June 2016|language=sl-SI}}</ref>\n| international = {{nowrap|[[Centrist Democrat International]]}}<br />[[International Democrat Union]]\n| european = [[European People's Party]]\n| europarl = [[European People's Party Group|European People's Party]]\n| colours = {{color box|{{Slovenian Democratic Party/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} [[Yellow]] {{color box|#133C8B|border=darkgray}} [[Blue]]\n| anthem = <center>\"Slovenska pomlad\"<ref>https://www.sds.si/o-stranki/soj</ref><br />{{small|\"Slovenian Spring\"}}[[File:Slovenska pomlad.ogg|197px|Slovenska pomlad]]</center>\n| seats1_title = [[Slovenian National Assembly|National Assembly]]\n| seats1 = {{composition bar|26|90|hex={{Slovenian Democratic Party/meta/color}}}}\n| seats2_title = [[European Parliament]]\n| seats2 = {{composition bar|2|8|hex={{Slovenian Democratic Party/meta/color}}}}\n| seats3_title = Mayors\n| seats3 = {{Composition bar|17|212|hex={{Slovenian Democratic Party/meta/color}}}}\n| seats4_title = Municipal council\n| seats4 = {{Composition bar|537|2750|hex={{Slovenian Democratic Party/meta/color}}}}\n| flag = [[File:Flag of the Slovenian Democratic Party.svg|225px|border|Flag of the Slovenian Democratic Party]]\n| website = {{url|sds.si}}\n| country = Slovenia\n}}\nThe '''Slovenian Democratic Party''' ({{lang-sl|Slovenska demokratska stranka}}, SDS), formerly the '''Social Democratic Party of Slovenia''' ({{lang-sl|Socialdemokratska stranka Slovenije}}, SDSS),<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://siol.net/novice/volitve-2018/slovenska-demokratska-stranka-sds-466986|title=SLOVENSKA DEMOKRATSKA STRANKA (SDS)|access-date=2018-06-04|language=sl}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rtvslo.si/gremvolit/stranke-in-liste/sds-vec-svobode-clovekovih-pravic-in-solidarnosti/453598|title=SDS: Ve\u010d svobode, \u010dlovekovih pravic in solidarnosti|work=Grem Volit|access-date=2018-06-04|language=sl-SI}}</ref> is a [[Slovenian nationalism|nationalist]]<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/jun/03/anti-immigration-party-leads-exit-poll-in-slovenian-election</ref> [[Right-wing populism|right-wing populist]]<ref>https://www.europeaninterest.eu/article/slovenia-parties-expected-elect-meps/</ref> [[List of political parties in Slovenia|political party]] in [[Slovenia]]. Led by [[Janez Jan\u0161a]], the SDS is a member of the [[European People's Party]] (EPP),<ref name=\":25\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.demsoc.org/2014/05/19/slovenian-democratic-party-sds/|title=Slovenian Democratic Party (SDS) {{!}} The Democratic Society|website=www.demsoc.org|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref> [[Centrist Democrat International]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://idc-cdi.com/en/parties/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170922103407/https://idc-cdi.com/en/parties/|url-status=live|archive-date=2017-09-22|title=Partidos Archivo - idc-cdi|date=2017-09-22|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref> and [[International Democrat Union]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.idu.org/members/|title=Members {{!}} International Democrat Union|website=www.idu.org|language=en-US|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n=== Origins ===\nThe Slovenian Democratic Party developed from the merger of two distinct political parties, being the legal successor of both of the [[Social Democratic Union of Slovenia]] and the [[Slovenian Democratic Union]],<ref name=\"Guardiancich2012\">{{cite book|author=Igor Guardiancich|title=Pension Reforms in Central, Eastern and Southeastern Europe: From Post-Socialist Transition to the Global Financial Crisis|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=APcO_fndhx0C&pg=PA194|year=2012|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-22595-6|page=194}}</ref><ref name=\":46\">{{Cite book|title=Reforming Europe : the role of the centre-right|date=2009|publisher=Springer-Verlag|others=Arvanitopoulos, K\u014dnstantinos., Centre for European Studies (Brussels, Belgium), Institouto D\u0113mokratias K\u014dnstantinos Karamanl\u0113s.|isbn=9783642005602|location=Berlin|oclc=659560461}}</ref><ref name=\":47\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.delo.si/novice/slovenija/umrl-je-prvi-predsednik-sds-france-tomsic.html|title=Umrl je prvi predsednik SDS France Tom\u0161i\u010d|date=2010-03-25|website=www.delo.si|language=sl-si|access-date=2019-01-25}}</ref><ref name=\":48\">{{Cite web|url=https://siol.net/novice/slovenija/pred-20-leti-je-bila-ustanovljena-slovenska-demokraticna-zveza-54747|title=Pred 20 leti je bila ustanovljena Slovenska demokrati\u010dna zveza|date=2009-01-11|website=siol.net|language=sl|access-date=2019-01-25}}</ref> member parties of the [[Democratic Opposition of Slovenia|Democratic Opposition of Slovenia (DEMOS)]] which defeated the [[Communist Party of Slovenia]]-derived parties in the first democratic Slovenian election in 1990,<ref name=\":46\" /> and carried out the [[democratization]] of Slovenia and its [[History of Slovenia#Disintegration of Yugoslavia|secession from Yugoslavia]].{{Citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\nThe Social Democratic Union of Slovenia had emerged from an independent, [[Anti-communism|anti-Communist]] trade union movement in the late 1980s. Its first president was the trade union leader [[France Tom\u0161i\u010d]], who in December 1987 organized a milestone workers' strike which lead to the establishment of an independent trade union, Neodvisnost, thus following the example of the [[Solidarity (Polish trade union)|Solidarity]] movement in [[Poland]],<ref name=\":51\" /> and, in 1989, the party (which was the first opposition party in the former communist world).<ref name=\":47\" /><ref name=\":50\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rtvslo.si/slovenija/umrl-je-france-tomsic/226566|title=Umrl je France Tom\u0161i\u010d|website=RTVSLO.si|language=sl|access-date=2019-01-25}}</ref><ref name=\":51\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.slovenija2001.gov.si/10years/path/memories/tomsic/|title=France Tomsic|website=www.slovenija2001.gov.si|access-date=2019-01-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.24ur.com/novice/slovenija/umrl-france-tomsic.html|title=Umrl France Tom\u0161i\u010d|date=2010-03-25|website=www.24ur.com|access-date=2019-01-25}}</ref> Tom\u0161i\u010d was replaced as leader by [[Jo\u017ee Pu\u010dnik]] later that year while the SDU was renamed as Social Democratic Party of Slovenia (SDS).<ref name=\":50\" /> Pu\u010dnik was a former dissident who had been forced to emigrate to Germany as a political exile in the 1960s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rtvslo.si/slovenija/politicni-disident-ki-je-postal-kljucni-akter-osamosvojitve/299999|title=Politi\u010dni disident, ki je postal klju\u010dni akter osamosvojitve|website=RTVSLO.si|language=sl|access-date=2019-01-25}}</ref> Under Pu\u010dnik's leadership, The SDU gradually developed into a moderate [[social democracy|social-democratic]] party, which combined the plea for a [[social market economy]] with the support of a [[welfare state]] based on a [[German model|German]], [[Economy of Austria|Austrian]] and [[Scandinavian welfare model|Scandinavian]] social model.{{Citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\nThe Slovenian Democratic Union was founded in January 1989<ref name=\":48\" /> as opposition to the [[Communist Party of Slovenia]], emphasizing establishment of the [[rule of law]] and respect for [[human rights]] and fundamental political freedoms, respect for [[minority rights]], and Euro-Atlantic integration (the [[European Union]] and [[NATO]]). It functioned as a broad but somewhat fragmented coalition of several groups with different [[liberalism|liberal]], [[social liberalism|social-liberal]] and [[civic nationalism|civic nationalist]] agendas.{{Citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\nIn 1991, after a conflict between the leadership and membership of SDU, the Slovenian Democratic Union split into two parties \u2013 the [[social liberalism|social-liberal]] wing established the [[Democratic Party (Slovenia)|Democratic Party]] (DSS), while the [[conservatism|conservative]] faction founded the [[National Democratic Party (Slovenia)|National Democratic Party]] (NDS).<ref name=\":48\" /> Members who did not join one of these two parties joined the Social Democratic Party led by [[Jo\u017ee Pu\u010dnik]].{{Citation needed|date=January 2019}} Although the Social Democratic Party suffered a clear defeat in the 1992 election, barely entering [[Slovenian National Assembly|Parliament]], it formed a coalition with the winning [[Liberal Democracy of Slovenia]] (LDS) and entered the cabinet of [[Janez Drnov\u0161ek]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://siol.net/novice/volitve-2018/drnovsek-je-leta-1992-med-zive-vrnil-janeza-janso-469978|title=Drnov\u0161ek je leta 1992 med \u017eive vrnil Janeza Jan\u0161o|date=2018-06-13|website=siol.net|language=sl|access-date=2019-01-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mladina.si/92312/apokalipsa-politicne-krize/|title=Apokalipsa politi\u010dne krize|website=Mladina.si|access-date=2019-01-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vlada.si/o_vladi/pretekle_vlade/|title=Pretekle vlade|website=www.vlada.si|language=en|access-date=2019-01-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mladina.si/92470/potapljanje-vladajoce-stranke/|title=Potapljanje vladajo\u010de stranke|website=Mladina.si|access-date=2019-01-25}}</ref><ref name=\":52\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.delo.si/novice/volitve/kratka-zgodovina-stranke-sds.html|title=Kratka zgodovina stranke SDS|date=2011-12-04|website=www.delo.si|language=sl-si|access-date=2019-01-25}}</ref>\n\n[[Janez Jan\u0161a|Jan\u0161a]] became party leader in 1993{{Citation needed|date=April 2019}} after Jo\u017ee Pu\u010dnik resigned due to health issues (Pu\u010dnik later became the honorary president of the party, a function he held until his death in January 2003).<ref name=\":52\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dnevnik.si/292103|title=Obele\u017eujemo peto obletnico smrti Jo\u017eeta Pu\u010dnika|website=Dnevnik|access-date=2019-01-25}}</ref> In 1995, the [[National Democratic Party (Slovenia)|National Democratic Party]] joined SDS, which thus became one of the legal successors of the [[Slovenian Democratic Union]].<ref name=\"Guardiancich2012\" /><ref name=\":48\" /><ref name=\":52\" />\n\nJanez Jan\u0161a was dismissed by Prime Minister Janez Drnov\u0161ek from his role as Defence Minister in 1994 because of his involvement in the [[Depala Vas]] affair (which centered around an incident in which military personnel arrested and mistreated an off-duty undercover police associate that was attempting to obtain classified documents about the Ministry of Defence).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sta.si/1990700/dve-desetletji-od-afere-depala-vas|title=STA: Dve desetletji od afere Depala vas|website=www.sta.si|access-date=2019-01-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://siol.net/novice/slovenija/to-so-najodmevnejse-afere-slovenskih-obvescevalcev-389567|title=To so najodmevnej\u00c5\u00a1e afere slovenskih obve\u00c5\u00a1\u00c4evalcev|website=siol.net|language=sl|access-date=2019-01-25}}</ref><ref name=\":52\" /> SDS subsequently left the Drnov\u0161ek government as a result.<ref name=\":52\" /> A 2003 [[Mladina]] article alleged that Slovenia's military's special unit (MORiS) was in 1994 performing military exercises intended to prepare the force to carry out a military [[coup d'\u00e9tat]]. The police force was at the same time covertly preparing to secure the state and prevent military takeover. In a press conference shortly prior to the article's publication, Jan\u0161a pointed to documents detailing these police plans to secure state institutions to argue that a coup was in fact afoot against his Ministry. In a 1999 interview with [[Delo (newspaper)|Delo]], Jan\u0161a commented the events of 1994 by saying: \"I held immense power in my hands. [...] And in 1994, when they were deposing me, there was a lot of suggestions that we not accept this removal. I could have done that. But I didn't.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mladina.si/92437/desant-na-ministrstvo/|title=Desant na ministrstvo|website=Mladina.si|access-date=2019-04-07}}</ref>\n\nSDS remained in opposition for the next 10 years, except for a brief period in 2000, when it entered a short-lived centre-right government led by [[Andrej Bajuk]],<ref name=\":52\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rtvslo.si/slovenija/hitre-zamenjave-v-cerarjevi-vladi-pada-ze-peti-minister/361871|title=Hitre zamenjave v Cerarjevi vladi. Pada \u017ee peti minister.|website=RTVSLO.si|language=sl|access-date=2019-01-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www2.24ur.com/bin/article_print.php?id=3139870|title=24ur.com - '1000 evrov pokojnine je predvolilna la\u017e'|website=www2.24ur.com|access-date=2019-01-25}}</ref> while gaining popularity among \u2013 as described by one of its [[Slovenian Democratic Party#Former supporters|former supporters]], [[Peter Jambrek]] \u2013 \"lower, frustrated social strata\".{{Citation needed|date=January 2019}}<ref>[http://www.dnevnik.si/clanek/1042482825 Peter Jambrek o tem, da je SDS stranka frustriranih ni\u017ejih slojev], Dnevnik, 25. Cctober 2011</ref>\n\n=== Radical populist turn ===\nAfter the year 2000, the party applied for membership in the [[European People's Party]] (EPP),<ref name=\":52\" /> adopting a [[economic liberalism|liberal]] economic policy and later pro-[[austerity]] measures upon the late-2000 economic crisis, while retaining an [[atlanticism|atlantist]] foreign policy.{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}} The rightward shift culminated in the 2003 name change from Social Democratic Party to Slovenian Democratic party.<ref name=\"HlousekKopecek\" /><ref name=\"Guardiancich2012\" />\n\nThe party's [[Political radicalism|radical]] [[populism]], [[nationalism|nationalistic]]<ref name=\"HlousekKopecek\"/> and [[xenophobia|xenophobic]] rhetoric was noticed also by political scientists.<ref name=\"Rizman\">{{Citation |first=Rudolf M. |last=Rizman |title=Radical Right Politics in Slovenia |work=The radical right in Central and Eastern Europe since 1989 |publisher=Penn State Press |year=1999 |pages=155\u2013162 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=QZr1vsDIvlUC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=slovenian%20democratic%20party&f=false |accessdate=14 November|isbn=0271043792 }}</ref><ref>{{Citation |first1=Ian |last1=Hall |first2=Magali |last2=Perrault |title=The Re-Austrianisation of Central Europe? |journal=Central Europe Review |volume=2 |number=13 |date=3 April 2000 |url=http://www.ce-review.org/00/13/essay13.html |accessdate=14 November 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Citation |first=Rudolf M. |last=Rizman |title=Uncertain path: Democratic transition and consolidation in Slovenia |publisher=Texas A&M University Press |year=2006 |page=74 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=0F5l-gI0_igC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=slovenian%20democratic%20party%20jansa&f=false |accessdate=14 November 2011|isbn=9781585444236 }}</ref> Moreover, the local Slovenian [[Catholic Church]] supported it more than any other Slovenian political party. Even though not a nominally Christian party, the local church has stood fully and unconditionally behind it.<ref name=\"Rizman\"/>\n\n=== 2004\u20132008: in power (first Jan\u0161a Cabinet) ===\nOn 3 October 2004, SDS won the [[2004 Slovenian parliamentary election|2004 parliamentary election]] with 29.1% of the popular vote and 29 out of 88 seats.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dvk-rs.si/arhivi/dz2004/en/index.htm|title=Republic of Slovenia Elections for Deputies to the National Assembly 2004|website=www.dvk-rs.si|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref> SDS then formed [[Cabinet of Janez Jan\u0161a I|a coalition]] with [[New Slovenia]] (NSi), the [[Slovenian People's Party]] (SLS), and [[Democratic Party of Pensioners of Slovenia]] (DeSUS), holding a total of 49 parliamentary seats (out of 90).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.rtvslo.si/volitve-v-dz/pregled-mandata-2004-2005/90806|title=Pregled mandata 2004/2005|work=Prvi interaktivni multimedijski portal, MMC RTV Slovenija|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref>\n\nThe SDS-led government passed several pro-business measures, initiated the [[regionalisation]] of the country by giving more power to local governments, and, in order to please its coalition party, DeSUS - introduced economically non-sustainable changes in the pension system.{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\nSDS has been accused of catering to the interests of the Slovenian [[Roman Catholic Church]] in exchange for political support.<ref name=\":20\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mladina.si/92559/katoliska-drzava-drzavna-cerkev/|title=Katoli\u0161ka dr\u017eava, dr\u017eavna cerkev|work=Mladina.si|access-date=2018-06-05}}</ref> Nevertheless, the Church maintained a critical attitude towards some of the party's positions (the SDS-led Government has assumed a favourable attitude towards [[gambling]] tourism, [[Embryonic stem cell|stem cell]] research and passed a law recognizing [[Civil unions in Slovenia|same-sex civil unions]], all opposed by the Roman Catholic Church).{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\n==== Internal affairs ====\nThe government introduced measures to supervise, and to curtail the powers of the [[Slovenian Intelligence and Security Agency]]. The measures were strongly rebuked by the opposition and segments of the press as an attempt to discredit the secret intelligence service and cast a negative shadow on the policies of previous governments.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mladina.si/92630/specialna-vojna/|title=Specialna vojna|work=Mladina.si|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.delo.si/novice/slovenija/komisiji-za-nadzor-sove-omejen-nadzor-v-tekocih-zadevah.html|title=Komisiji za nadzor Sove omejen nadzor v teko\u010dih zadevah|last=Uredni\u0161tvo|access-date=2018-06-03|language=sl-si}}</ref>\n\n==== Freedom of the press violations ====\nThe first SDS government was the target of widespread criticism due to allegations of meddling in the independence of the press.<ref name=\":35\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/04/world/europe/viktor-orban-media-slovenia.html|title=Safe in Hungary, Viktor Orban Pushes His Message Across Europe|date=2018-06-04|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-06-05|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The first SDS government has been accused of politicising the independent press by appointing political allies<ref name=\":39\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/europe-populists-right-wing-success-marine-le-pen-viktor-orban-italy-slovenia-a8382766.html|title=The right-wing populists doing well across Europe, from Marine Le Pen to Viktor Orban|work=The Independent|access-date=2018-06-08|language=en-GB}}</ref> to leadership and journalist positioned in the state [[Slovenian Press Agency]],<ref name=\":20\" /><ref name=\":21\" /> daily newspaper [[Delo (newspaper)|Delo]],<ref name=\":20\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.mladina.si/?__rewriter=1&id=108659&|title=J. J.? Ne, hvala!|work=Mladina.si|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref><ref name=\":21\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.dnevnik.si/1042713981/slovenija/jansev-medijski-projekt-kot-zadnje-volilno-upanje-sds|title=Jan\u0161ev medijski projekt kot zadnje volilno upanje SDS|work=Dnevnik|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref> regional newspaper [[Primorske novice]],<ref name=\":21\" /> and public media and broadcasting organisation, [[Radiotelevizija Slovenija|RTV Slovenia]].<ref name=\":20\" /><ref name=\":21\"/> State-owned companies also ceased purchasing adverts in the daily newspaper [[Dnevnik (Slovenia)|Dnevnik]] and weekly political magazine [[Mladina]], two publications critical of the administration.<ref name=\":59\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mladina.si/95386/politicni-prsti-v-oglasevalskem-kolacu/|title=Politi\u010dni prsti v ogla\u0161evalskem kola\u010du|website=Mladina.si|access-date=2019-04-07}}</ref><ref name=\":20\" /> By changing the laws governing the administration of the public broadcaster RTV Slovenia, the government enabled increased political control of the state media organisation's editorial board and its board of directors by increasing the number of board members appointed by the government.<ref name=\":20\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rtvslo.si/referendum-o-rtv/kaj-prinasa-novi-zakon/43432|title=Kaj prina\u0161a novi zakon?|work=Prvi interaktivni multimedijski portal, MMC RTV Slovenija|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref> The law faced a referendum challenge, but was approved by a tight margin as it also promised to lower compulsory contributions for the broadcaster's funding.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.24ur.com/novice/volitve/ce-iz-vseh-smetnjakov-po-mestih-gledajo-struce-kruha.html|title=Kako je bilo v Jan\u0161evi vladi?|website=www.24ur.com|language=sl|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref> In 2007, over five hundred journalists launched a petition against political pressures on the media. The petition accused premier Jan\u0161a of limiting press freedom in particular, but was also more broadly aimed against all infringements of press freedom by either government, political actors in general, or media company owners.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mladina.si/75880/04-10-2007-peticija_zoper_cenzuro_in_politicne_pritiske_na_novinarje_v_sloveniji/|title=Peticija zoper cenzuro in politi\u010dne pritiske na novinarje v Sloveniji|work=Mladina.si|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dnevnik.si/271330|title=Slovenski novinarji zoper cenzuro|work=Dnevnik|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref> The [[International Press Institute]] voiced support for the petition and called on the government to create an independent body to investigate the claims of media influence.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dnevnik.si/272383|title=Mednarodni novinarski in\u0161titut poziva k preiskavi politi\u010dnih pritiskov na slovenske medije|work=Dnevnik|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref>\n\nSDS rejected accusations of impropriety, claiming the media was in fact controlled by leftist opposition groups.<ref name=\":35\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dnevnik.si/285888|title=Jo\u017ee Tanko (SDS): Nekatere medije nadzira Borut Pahor|work=Dnevnik|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref>\n\n==== Economy and finance ====\nThe first [[Cabinet of Janez Jan\u0161a I|Cabinet of Janez Jan\u0161a]] oversaw a period of rapid economic growth. GDP grew by nearly 5% between 2004 and 2006, reaching nearly 7% growth in 2007,<ref name=\":2\" /> making Slovenia the fastest-growing eurozone member for that year.<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-slovenia-pm/slovenia-parliament-confirms-jansa-as-prime-minister-idUSTRE80R0L720120128|title=Slovenia parliament confirms Jansa as prime minister|last=Novak|first=Marja|work=U.S.|access-date=2018-06-03|language=en-US}}</ref> The economic boom, however, was highly dependent on private debt, particularly corporate debt.<ref name=\":2\" /> Additionally, the Jan\u0161a government failed to implement meaningful structural reforms or accumulate budget surpluses during the period of sustained growth, instead opting for [[pork barrel politics]], reducing tax burdens while engaging in economic populist overspending, making the country particularly susceptible to the coming [[Financial crisis of 2007\u20132008|economic crisis]].<ref name=\"Guardiancich2012\" />\n\n[[Andrej Bajuk]], Minister of Finance in Jan\u0161a's first cabinet, listed the passage of comprehensive tax reform (which included the lowering of corporate taxes and taxes on juridical persons, a reduction of the tax burden on individual incomes, the flattening of income tax margin progression, an increase in tax deductions, and a simplification of the tax code), overseeing the implementation of the Euro and the privatisation of state-owned NKBM bank, and reducing public expenditure as the greatest accomplishments of the ministry during his term (2004\u20132008).<ref name=\":49\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.dnevnik.si/337210|title=Dose\u017eki ministrstva za finance po Bajuku: Dav\u010dna reforma, uvedba evra, predsedovanje EU, privatizacija NKBM in zni\u017eanje javne porabe|work=Dnevnik|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Jan\u0161a, the most prominent economic challenge confronted by his government was a bout of inflation<ref name=\":53\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rtvslo.si/gospodarstvo/inflacija-edini-slab-kazalec/79214|title=Inflacija edini slab kazalec|website=RTVSLO.si|language=sl|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref> (which occurred during the 2007-08 period and was steepest for foodstuff prices).<ref name=\":54\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rtvslo.si/gospodarstvo/skok-letne-inflacije-na-6-9-odstotka/85470|title=Skok letne inflacije na 6,9 odstotka|website=RTVSLO.si|language=sl|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref><ref name=\":53\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rtvslo.si/slovenija/inflacija-vezana-na-cene-hrane/81460|title=Inflacija vezana na cene hrane|website=RTVSLO.si|language=sl|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref><ref name=\"siol.net\">{{Cite web|url=https://siol.net/letna-stopnja-inflacije-v-sloveniji-7-odstotna-313430|title=Letna stopnja inflacije v Sloveniji 7 odstotna|website=siol.net|language=sl|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref> At the close of 2007, the inflation rate in Slovenia was the highest of any Eurozone member.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.24ur.com/novice/gospodarstvo/visje-cene-visja-inflacija.html|title=Vi\u0161je cene, vi\u0161ja inflacija|website=www.24ur.com|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref> Jan\u0161a, Finance Minister Bajuk and other government officials pointed to high oil prices and a non-competitive internal food market as the main underlying causes for the inflation.<ref name=\":53\" /><ref name=\":49\" /><ref name=\"siol.net\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.delo.si/novice/slovenija/dz-vzrok-za-inflacijo-na-strani-ponudbe.html|title=DZ: Vzrok za inflacijo na strani ponudbe|last=Uredni\u0161tvo|date=2008-02-14|website=www.delo.si|language=sl-si|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref><ref name=\":54\" /> Jan\u0161a faced criticism for his statement regarding the issue made during a gathering of regional politicians and businessmen; Jan\u0161a dismissed concerns regarding rising food prices, saying that \"as long as there are loaves of bread in every city dumpster the situation isn't alarming\".<ref name=\":55\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dnevnik.si/274740|title=Ostri odzivi na izjavo premiera Janeza Jan\u0161e o \u0161trucah v smetnjakih|website=Dnevnik|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rtvslo.si/slovenija/jansa-odgovarjal-poslancem/78137|title=Jan\u0161a odgovarjal poslancem|website=RTVSLO.si|language=sl|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref> Economic Development Minister Andrej Vizjak similarly addressed cost of living concerns by saying that citizens \"should not be loathe to occasionally eat yesterday's bread\", going on to say that the food price increases are an opportunity to address the overindulgence of Slovenian consumers.<ref name=\":55\" />\n\n=== 2008\u20132011: in opposition ===\nIn the [[2008 Slovenian parliamentary election|2008 parliamentary election]] (held on 21 September 2008) narrowly lost against the [[Social Democrats (Slovenia)|Social Democrats]], until then the main opposition party. It also lost one seat in Slovenian Parliament, falling to 28.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dvk-rs.si/index.php/si/arhiv-drzavni-zbor-rs/leto-2008|title=Dr\u017eavni zbor RS - Leto 2008 {{!}} Dr\u017eavna volilna komisija|website=Dr\u017eavna volilna komisija|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref>\n\nWith the election of the Social Democrat leader [[Borut Pahor]] as Prime Minister of Slovenia, the Slovenian Democratic Party officially declared it would stay in opposition and form a [[shadow cabinet]]. The shadow government was formed in late December 2008, and it includes several independent members as well as members from other conservative parties.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sta.si/vest.php?s=s&id=1349433 |title=STA: SDS ustanovila strokovni svet |publisher=Sta.si |date=2008-12-23 |accessdate=2014-07-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714152831/http://www.sta.si/vest.php?s=s&id=1349433 |archivedate=2014-07-14 }}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2009 European Parliament election in Slovenia|2009 European election]], the SDS was the most popular party in Slovenia with 26.9% of votes, more than eight points ahead of the second-most popular party, the ruling Social Democrats.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dvk-rs.si/index.php/si/arhiv-evropski-parlament/leto-2009|title=Volitve v Evropski parlament - Leto 2009 {{!}} Dr\u017eavna volilna komisija|website=Dr\u017eavna volilna komisija|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, the MP [[Franc Puk\u0161i\u010d]] left the Slovenian Democratic Party and joined the [[Slovenian People's Party]]; the SDS parliamentary group was thus reduced from 28 to 27 MPs.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.rtvslo.si/slovenija/franc-puksic-iz-sds-a-v-sls/213371|title=Franc Puk\u0161i\u010d iz SDS-a v SLS?|work=Prvi interaktivni multimedijski portal, MMC RTV Slovenija|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref>\n\n=== 2012\u20132013: a year in power (second Jan\u0161a Cabinet) ===\nIn the [[2011 Slovenian parliamentary election|2011 snap parliamentary election]] (held on 4 December after the centre-left governing coalition collapsed due to internal conflict and inefficacy in passing meaningful economic reforms), SDS won 26.19% of the vote, gaining 26 seats in the [[National Assembly (Slovenia)|National Assembly]], thus making SDS the second-largest parliamentary party after the newly formed [[centre-left]] party, [[Positive Slovenia]] (PS) (headed by Ljubljana mayor [[Zoran Jankovi\u0107 (politician)|Zoran Jankovi\u0107]]), which won 28 MPs (28.5% of the total).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sloveniatimes.com/exit-poll-jankovic-wins-the-elections/2|title=Positive Slovenia Surprise Winner of Election|website=www.sloveniatimes.com|language=sl|access-date=2018-06-02}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-slovenia-pm/slovenia-parliament-confirms-jansa-as-prime-minister-idUSTRE80R0L720120128|title=Slovenia parliament confirms Jansa as prime minister|last=Novak|first=Marja|work=U.S.|access-date=2018-06-02|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\":17\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.britannica.com/place/Slovenia/Government-and-society#ref1007089|title=Slovenia - Government and society|encyclopedia=Encyclopedia Britannica|access-date=2018-06-03|language=en}}</ref> However, SDS succeeded in forming a ruling [[Cabinet of Janez Jan\u0161a II|four-party coalition government]] (which included the [[Civic List (Slovenia)|Civic List]], [[New Slovenia]], [[Slovenian People's Party]], and [[Democratic Party of Pensioners of Slovenia]]) (holding a combined total of 50 out of 90 parliamentary seats) some two months after the election after PS failed to form a coalition with a parliamentary majority. The coalition took power amid an alarming economic downturn ([[European debt crisis]]),<ref name=\":0\" /> the worst in the independent country's history.{{citation needed|date=June 2018}}  The country's economic woes were further exacerbated by credit agencies' lowering of Slovenia's credit rating amid the political tumult.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe coalition, headed by SDS, undertook drastic economic and financial reforms in an attempt to halt the economic downturn. Finance Minister Janez \u0160u\u0161tar\u0161i\u010d pledged to speed up privatisation of state enterprises, cut public spending, and reduce budget shortfalls.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/slovenia-finmin-idUSFINMINSI20120215|title=PROFILE-Slovenia's Finance Minister Janez Sustersic|last=Editorial|first=Reuters|work=U.S.|access-date=2018-06-03|language=en-US}}</ref> Jan\u0161a additionally pledged to cut taxes, remove regulations, lower the deficit, and raise the retirement age.<ref name=\":16\" /> The coalition passed laws transferring all state-owned enterprises into a single state holding company to accelerate privatisation efforts, and created a bad bank that would take on non-performing loans from the bad debt-ridden state-owned banks.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-slovenia-reforms/slovenia-adopts-reform-laws-but-referendums-possible-idUSBRE89M1EP20121023|title=Slovenia adopts reform laws but referendums possible|last=Novak|first=Marja|work=U.S.|access-date=2018-06-02|language=en-US}}</ref> It intended to cut profit and income taxes to boost the economy,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sloveniatimes.com/there-is-no-choice|title=There is no Choice|website=www.sloveniatimes.com|language=sl|access-date=2018-06-02}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/slovenia-economy/slovenia-expects-eu-assessment-mission-in-april-finmin-idUSL5E8E89PS20120308|title=Slovenia expects EU assessment mission in April-finmin|last=Editorial|first=Reuters|work=U.S.|access-date=2018-06-02|language=en-US}}</ref> and enact [[Balanced budget amendment|constitutional changes demanding balance budgets]].<ref name=\":1\" /> It also passed sweeping and highly contentious austerity measures (the Law of Public Finance Balance (Slovene: ''Zakon o uravnove\u0161enju javnih financ'' (''ZUJF''))), and reportedly planned further cuts to state spending.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.eurofound.europa.eu/observatories/eurwork/articles/industrial-relations/austerity-measures-cause-conflict|title=Austerity measures cause conflict {{!}} Eurofound|website=www.eurofound.europa.eu|language=en|access-date=2018-06-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2012-05-11/news/sns-rt-slovenia-budgeturgentl5e8gb69w-20120511_1_slovenia-austerity-measures-fiscal-gap|title=Recession-hit Slovenia adopts austerity measures|work=tribunedigital-chicagotribune|access-date=2018-06-02|language=en}}</ref> The ''ZUJF'' fiscal consolidation law included provisions lowering pensions (widely opposed by the public<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sloveniatimes.com/poll-three-quarters-of-slovenians-say-pension-cuts-unjustified|title=Poll: Three Quarters of Slovenians Say Pension Cuts Unjustified|website=www.sloveniatimes.com|language=sl|access-date=2018-06-02}}</ref>), cutting wages for public sector employees, reducing education funding, social transfers and benefits.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sloveniatimes.com/national-assembly-starts-debate-on-austerity-bills|title=National Assembly Starts Debate on Austerity Bills|website=www.sloveniatimes.com|language=sl|access-date=2018-06-02}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-slovenia-austerity/slovenian-austerity-drive-threatened-by-referendum-call-idUSBRE84H09N20120518|title=Slovenian austerity drive threatened by referendum call|last=Novak|first=Marja|work=U.S.|access-date=2018-06-02|language=en-US}}</ref> The draft of the law sparked a public sector general strike,<ref name=\":2\" /> and the law faced the possibility of a referendum.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sloveniatimes.com/referendum-on-austerity-act|title=Referendum on Austerity Act?|website=www.sloveniatimes.com|language=sl|access-date=2018-06-02}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" />\n\nThe SDS-led government proved impotent in stemming the economic troubles facing the nation. Despite the momentous reforms efforts, the economic troubles intensified, resulting in increasing levels of unemployment, plunging living standards, a fall in domestic spending, and large budget deficits.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-slovenia-government/struggling-slovenia-to-appoint-new-pm-to-rescue-economy-idUSBRE91P0EE20130226|title=Struggling Slovenia to appoint new PM to rescue economy|last=Editorial|first=Reuters|work=U.S.|access-date=2018-06-02|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":17\" /> The fall in domestic demand, coupled with falling exports, resulted in a [[double dip recession]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-slovenia-protest/protests-in-slovenia-continue-despite-governments-fall-idUSBRE9280EU20130309|title=Protests in Slovenia continue despite government's fall|last=Novak|first=Marja|work=U.S.|access-date=2018-06-02|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-slovenia-protest/fresh-slovenian-protests-amid-bailout-fears-idUSBRE93Q05Y20130427|title=Fresh Slovenian protests amid bailout fears|last=Novak|first=Marja|work=U.S.|access-date=2018-06-03|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/financialcrisis/9960610/Slovenia-faces-contagion-from-Cyprus-as-banking-crisis-deepens.html|title=Slovenia faces contagion from Cyprus as banking crisis deepens|last=Evans-Pritchard|first=Ambrose|journal=Daily Telegraph|date=2013-03-28|access-date=2018-06-03|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> A later report alleges that the sharp downturn in Slovenian economic outlook was a result of Jan\u0161a's overdramatic public statements regarding the economic fitness of the nation. Jan\u0161a reportedly made such ominous claims for political purposes as means of solidifying political power and as a negotiating strategy to strengthen his hand during negotiations with public sector unions. The PM's eerie pronouncements were taken at face value by foreign observers, however, creating a self-fulfilling feedback loop where gloomy statements made by top Slovene officials created more panic and dismay in the foreign press and various organisations, and vice versa, resulting in falling credit ratings and asset prices, and excessive capital injections/bailouts with funds borrowed at excessively high interest rates.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mladina.si/176754/kdo-je-pokopal-slovenijo/|title=Kdo je pokopal Slovenijo?|work=Mladina.si|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref>\n\nJan\u0161a also faced graft charges even before ascending to the premiership in 2012. He was one of the defendants being tried for corruption as result of a [[Patria case|2006 bribery scandal]] involving charges of accepting kickbacks to fund his party's electoral campaign.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://euobserver.com/investigations/123961|title=[Investigation] Arms deals and bribes: The downfall of Slovenia's former PM|access-date=2018-06-02|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn late 2012, [[2012\u201313 Maribor protests|protests began to take place]] in Slovenia's second largest city, Maribor, against its mayor and SDS ally, [[Franc Kangler]], who was being investigated due to allegations of corruption.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-slovenia-protests/slovenia-as-star-wanes-anger-on-streets-idUSBRE8BJ0UU20121220|title=Slovenia: as star wanes, anger on streets|last=Radosavljevic|first=Zoran|work=U.S.|access-date=2018-06-02|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-slovenia-protests/violent-mass-protest-continue-in-slovenia-idUSBRE8B218Q20121203|title=Violent mass protest continue in Slovenia|last=Novak|first=Marja|work=U.S.|access-date=2018-06-02|language=en-US}}</ref> The protests soon picked up momentum and [[2012\u201313 Slovenian protests|spread across the country]], becoming the largest in the independent republic's history. Protestors' main grievances were the harsh austerity measures imposed by the ruling government, looming sale-offs of state enterprises, and allegations of widespread corruption among the ruling elite. The protests also saw the worst violence in the nation's history as an independent state, with small groups of young, violent extremists - likely members of far-right and hooligan groups - clashing with police.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dw.com/en/thousands-protest-against-austerity-in-slovenia/a-16387391|title=Thousands protest against austerity in Slovenia {{!}} DW {{!}} 18.11.2012|last=(www.dw.com)|first=Deutsche Welle|website=DW.COM|language=en|access-date=2018-06-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-slovenia-protest/slovenia-police-clash-with-protesters-ahead-of-vote-idUSBRE8AT1GD20121130|title=Slovenia police clash with protesters ahead of vote|last=Novak|first=Marja|work=U.S.|access-date=2018-06-02|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/anti-austerity-slovenia-protesters-clash-with-police-1.1298756|title=Anti-austerity Slovenia protesters clash with police {{!}} CBC News|work=CBC|access-date=2018-06-02|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-slovenia-arrests/slovenia-police-arrest-141-in-violent-anti-austerity-protests-idUSBRE8B30QM20121204|title=Slovenia police arrest 141 in violent anti-austerity protests|last=Editorial|first=Reuters|work=U.S.|access-date=2018-06-02|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\":17\" /> In early 2013, the instability and public resentment was compounded after the [[Commission for the Prevention of Corruption of the Republic of Slovenia|Commission for the Prevention of Corruption]] revealed both PM Janez Jan\u0161a and the leader of the largest opposition party (PS), [[Zoran Jankovi\u0107 (politician)|Zoran Jankovi\u0107]], violated anti-corruption laws by failing to report or account for assets in their possession and received income/payments.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sloveniatimes.com/watchdog-finds-jansa-jankovic-in-violation-of-anti-graft-law|title=Watchdog Finds Jan\u0161a, Jankovi\u0107 in Violation of Anti-Graft Law|website=www.sloveniatimes.com|language=sl|access-date=2018-06-02}}</ref><ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-slovenia-crisis/slovenia-gripped-by-strike-government-on-the-ropes-idUSBRE90M0KQ20130123|title=Slovenia gripped by strike, government on the ropes|last=Novak|first=Marja|work=U.S.|access-date=2018-06-02|language=en-US}}</ref> Media reports alleging [[Slovenian Intelligence and Security Agency]] was \"infiltrated\" by members of SDS also surfaced.<ref name=\"SOVA_biased\">[http://www.mladina.si/119717/vdor-kadrov-sds-v-sovo/ An Intrusion of the Members of SDS into Sova] (In Slovene: \"Vdor kadrov SDS v Sovo\"), [[Mladina]], 18 January 2013</ref> Amid continuing anti-government protests,<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-slovenia-protests/slovenia-protest-adds-pressure-to-crumbling-government-idUSBRE9170XI20130208|title=Slovenia protest adds pressure to crumbling government|last=Novak|first=Marja|work=U.S.|access-date=2018-06-02|language=en-US}}</ref> a strike of public sector workers,<ref name=\"auto2\"/> and the lowest public opinion ratings of any government in the nation's history,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ninamedia.si/drzavnizbor.php|title=Ninamedia - Arhiv anket|website=www.ninamedia.si|access-date=2018-06-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.delo.si/novice/politika/anketa-dela-stranke-z-vse-manjso-podporo.html|title=Anketa Dela: Stranke z vse manj\u0161o podporo|last=politika|first=Marko Pe\u010dauer, notranja|access-date=2018-06-22|language=sl-si}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.delo.si/novice/politika/anketa-dela-velikanska-podpora-protikorupcijski-komisiji.html|title=Anketa Dela: Velikanska podpora protikorupcijski komisiji|last=politika|first=Marko Pe\u010dauer, notranja|access-date=2018-06-22|language=sl-si}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mladina.si/120542/za-jansev-odhod/|title=Za Jan\u0161ev odhod!|work=Mladina.si|access-date=2018-06-22}}</ref> coalition partners began to depart from the coalition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.delo.si/novice/politika/sls-ce-jansa-do-februarja-ne-odstopi-gremo-iz-koalicije-tudi-mi.html|title=SLS: \u010de Jan\u0161a do februarja ne odstopi gremo iz koalicije tudi mi|date=2013-01-14}}</ref><ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\"auto1\"/> The government finally collapsed after a vote of no confidence, and a PS consensus candidate, [[Alenka Bratu\u0161ek]], was appointed as PM despite continuing protests demanding a snap election.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-slovenia-government/slovenian-coalition-party-asks-premier-to-resign-idUSBRE90B0FG20130112|title=Slovenian coalition party asks premier to resign|last=Novak|first=Marja|work=U.S.|access-date=2018-06-02|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\":28\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.sloveniatimes.com/alenka-bratusek-new-pm-designate|title=Alenka Bratu\u0161ek New PM-designate|website=www.sloveniatimes.com|language=sl|access-date=2018-06-02}}</ref><ref name=\":4\"/><ref name=\":17\"/>\n\n=== 2013\u20132020: return to opposition ===\nOn 20 March 2013, the second Jan\u0161a cabinet was replaced by the [[cabinet of Alenka Bratu\u0161ek]], a four-party centre-left coalition led by the new leader of [[Positive Slovenia]], [[Alenka Bratu\u0161ek]].<ref name=\":28\"/><ref name=\":4\"/><ref name=\":17\"/>\n\nIn June 2013, Jan\u0161a was convicted in the [[Patria case]], but appealed the verdict. In April 2014, the Higher Court upheld the two-year jail sentence passed on Janez Jan\u0161a as result of the bribery conviction.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-slovenia-corruption/slovenian-court-confirms-jail-sentence-for-ex-pm-jansa-idUSBREA3R0UL20140428|title=Slovenian court confirms jail sentence for ex-PM Jansa|last=Editorial|first=Reuters|work=U.S.|access-date=2018-06-04|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.economist.com/eastern-approaches/2014/05/03/slovenias-fragile-recovery|title=Slovenia's fragile recovery|journal=The Economist|language=en|access-date=2018-06-04|date=2014-05-03}}</ref> In June of that year, Jan\u0161a began serving out his sentence, 26 years after his imprisonment for leaking military secrets as a whistle-blower ([[JBTZ trial|his imprisonment, trial, and public reaction]] were a milestone in the Slovenian path to independence). Despite his imprisonment, Jan\u0161a stood as candidate for MP.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sloveniatimes.com/after-26-years-jansa-in-prison-again|title=After 26 Years, Jan\u0161a in Prison Again|website=www.sloveniatimes.com|language=sl|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref>\n\nIn the May [[2014 European Parliament election]], SDS came in first place nationally, garnering 24.78% of the vote,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.delo.si/assets/info5/20140525/EUvolitve2014/volitve.html |title=EU volitve 2014 / 18 |publisher=Delo.si |date= |accessdate=2014-07-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.volitve.gov.si/ep2014/en/rez_sl.html |title=European parliament elections 2014 |publisher=Volitve.gov.si |date=2014-05-25 |accessdate=2014-07-10}}</ref> and winning three [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]] seats (out of eight allocated for Slovenia).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.volitve.gov.si/ep2014/en/rez_kan.html |title=European parliament elections 2014 |publisher=Volitve.gov.si |date=2014-05-25 |accessdate=2014-07-10}}</ref>\n\nThe party received 20.69% of the vote in the [[2014 Slovenian parliamentary election|snap Slovenian parliamentary election]] held on 13 July 2014, and won 21 seats in parliament.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://volitve.gov.si/dz2014/en/index.html|title=Republic of Slovenia early elections for deputies to the national assembly 2014|website=volitve.gov.si|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref> The party remained in opposition, this time to the [[cabinet of Miro Cerar]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sloveniatimes.com/slovenia-with-new-government|title=Slovenia With New Government|website=www.sloveniatimes.com|language=sl|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref> Janez Jan\u0161a was reelected as MP despite being imprisoned. The Constitutional Court decided not to deprive Jan\u0161a of his MP mandate, and Jan\u0161a was allowed leave while carrying out his political functions.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rtvslo.si/slovenija/jansa-ni-smel-iz-zapora-saj-ni-pojasnil-kaj-bo-pocel/352105|title=Jan\u0161a ni smel iz zapora, saj ni pojasnil, kaj bo po\u010del|work=Prvi interaktivni multimedijski portal, MMC RTV Slovenija|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref> The Constitutional Court suspended Jan\u0161a's jail sentence in December, pending the ruling regarding his appeal of the Patria verdict.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.delo.si/novice/politika/jansa-ni-vec-zapornik.html|title=Jan\u0161a za zdaj izpu\u0161\u010den iz zapora|last=Delo.si|first=Peter Jan\u010di\u010d, notranja politika, Ni. \u010c., Pi. K.|access-date=2018-06-04|language=sl-si}}</ref> The Constitutional Court decided to annul the Higher Court's decision in April 2015, returning it to the lower courts for retrial.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dnevnik.si/1042711773|title=Ustavno sodi\u0161\u010de razveljavilo dveletno zaporno kazen Janezu Jan\u0161i|work=Dnevnik|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref> In September of the same year, the statute of limitations of the Patria case expired.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-slovenia-corruption/slovenian-bribery-trial-against-ex-pm-jansa-expires-idUSKCN0R71KC20150907|title=Slovenian bribery trial against ex-PM Jansa expires|last=Editorial|first=Reuters|work=U.S.|access-date=2018-06-04|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nSDS representatives expressed the belief that the trial was politically motivated and that the imprisonment of the party frontman unfairly hindered their election efforts, declaring the elections illegitimate and \"stolen\", and demanded fresh elections.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sloveniatimes.com/insulted-and-defeated-sds-party-irrationally-smearing-their-own-country|title=Insulted and Defeated SDS Party Irrationally Smearing Their Own Country|website=www.sloveniatimes.com|language=sl|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref><ref name=\":29\" /><ref name=\"auto3\">{{Cite news|url=https://siol.net/novice/slovenija/jansa-na-sodiscu-volitve-2014-so-bile-ukradene-461818|title=SDS to\u017ei dr\u017eavo: \"Volitve 2014 so bile ukradene\"|access-date=2018-06-04|language=sl}}</ref> In 2018, SDS sued the state for alleged financial damages the party incurred due to the alleged election \"theft\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://english.sta.si/2440354/sds-patria-damages-trial-starting|title=STA: SDS Patria damages trial starting|website=english.sta.si|language=en|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref><ref name=\"auto3\"/> and lost the case.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://siol.net/novice/slovenija/sodisce-zavrnilo-odskodninsko-tozbo-sds-proti-drzavi-468215|title=Sodi\u0161\u010de zavrnilo od\u0161kodninsko to\u017ebo SDS proti dr\u017eavi|date=2018-05-23|work=Siol.net|access-date=2019-03-03|language=sl}}</ref>\n\nWith a campaign largely based on anti-immigration populist rhetoric, SDS topped public opinion polls heading into the 2018 parliamentary election.<ref name=\":8\" /> The incendiary electoral campaign sparked a rally under the title \"Without Fear \u2014 Against the Politics of Hatred\", with some 2,000-3,000 heart-shaped balloon-carrying marchers in attendance.<ref name=\":12\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vecer.com/spremljamo-v-ljubljani-protest-proti-sirjenju-sovrastva-6484656|title=(VIDEO in FOTO) Ve\u010d tiso\u010d ljudi na shodu proti politiki sovra\u0161tva|work=\u010casnik Ve\u010der d.o.o.|access-date=2018-06-07|language=sl-si}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://siol.net/novice/slovenija/protest-v-ljubljani-sejanje-strahu-sovraznost-in-lazi-vodi-v-totalitarizem-foto-469020|title=Protest v Ljubljani: \"Sejanje strahu, sovra\u017enosti in la\u017ei vodi v totalitarizem\" #foto|access-date=2018-06-07|language=sl}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 2018 electoral campaign, SDS also begun to send postable questionnaires (\"voter consults\") to Slovene households. The questionnaires contained loaded questions and proposals (e.g. \"... Do you support SDS's proposal that the healthcare system be set in order?\"). The effort was apparently part of the party's electoral campaign, and likely fashioned on Hungarian \"national consultations\", which the country's ruling party has practiced for years.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mladina.si/185151/posvetovanje-s-prevaro/|title=Posvetovanje s prevaro|work=Mladina.si|access-date=2018-06-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://vezjak.com/2018/05/28/dilema-izsiljene-izbire-ste-za-bozicnico/|title=Dilema izsiljene izbire: \"Ste za bo\u017ei\u010dnico?\"|date=2018-05-28|work=::: IN MEDIA RES|access-date=2018-06-10|language=sl-SI}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/76ce19e4-a768-11e7-93c5-648314d2c72c|title=Subscribe to read|website=Financial Times|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-06-10}}</ref>\n\nSDS once again emerged as winner in the [[2018 Slovenian parliamentary election|3 June 2018 parliamentary election]], garnering 24.92% of the vote and winning 25 MP seats.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://volitve.gov.si/dz2018/#/rezultati|title=http://volitve.gov.si/dz2018/#/rezultati|last=d.o.o.|first=SRC|website=volitve.gov.si|access-date=2018-06-17}}</ref> However, the party was unlikely to be able to shore up needed support for a governing coalition, as most parliamentary parties ([[List of Marjan \u0160arec]], [[Social Democrats (Slovenia)|Social Democrats]], [[Modern Centre Party]], [[The Left (Slovenia)|The Left]], [[Party of Alenka Bratu\u0161ek]], and [[Democratic Party of Pensioners of Slovenia]]) had declared that they would not participate in a coalition with SDS.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://siol.net/novice/volitve-2018/tudi-ce-se-jansa-umakne-sarec-ne-bi-sel-v-koalicijo-s-sds-468462|title=Tudi \u010de se Jan\u0161a umakne, \u0160arec ne bi \u0161el v koalicijo s SDS|last=Mlakar|first=Luka|date=2018-05-25|work=Siol.net|access-date=2019-02-05|language=sl}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rtvslo.si/slovenija/sarec-po-srecanju-s-cerarjem-obstaja-volja-da-v-koalicijo-z-sds-om-ne-gremo/457336|title=\u0160arec po sre\u010danju s Cerarjem: Obstaja volja, da v koalicijo z SDS-om ne gremo|date=2018-06-07|work=RTVSLO.si|access-date=2019-02-05|language=sl}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rtvslo.si/slovenija/sarec-po-srecanju-s-cerarjem-obstaja-volja-da-v-koalicijo-z-sds-om-ne-gremo/457336|title=Leva, desna ali mavri\u010dna koalicija? Nekatere so pre\u0161ibke, druge naporne|last=Zajc|first=Drago|date=2018-06-23|work=Delo|access-date=2019-02-05|language=sl}}</ref> Some two weeks after the 2018 election, Jan\u0161a again met with Hungarian PM Orb\u00e1n during a private visit in Budapest. Jan\u0161a and Orb\u00e1n also held a conference call with US president [[Donald Trump]] during the meeting.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://english.sta.si/2526124/sds-head-jansa-pays-visit-to-hungarian-pm-orban|title=STA: SDS head Jan\u0161a pays visit to Hungarian PM Orban|website=english.sta.si|language=en|access-date=2018-06-17}}</ref> Jan\u0161a stated he would be willing to relinquish his post as PM designate to some other SDS MP such a move would ease tensions and enable SDS to form a coalition government.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-slovenia-government/slovenias-president-to-give-mandate-to-anti-immigrant-party-to-form-government-idUSKCN1J31SI|title=Slovenia's president to give mandate to anti-immigrant party to...|last=Novak|first=Marja|work=U.S.|access-date=2018-06-17|language=en-US}}</ref> Despite the concession, the PM post was eventually occupied by the leader of the second largest parliamentary party, [[Marjan \u0160arec]], who succeeded in forming a centre-left [[minority government]] (without the participation of SDS).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/slovenian-comedian-gets-new-role-prime-minister-n901756|title=Comedian gets new role: prime minister of Slovenia|website=NBC News|language=en|access-date=2019-03-09}}</ref>\n\nAfter the 2018 parliamentary election, SDS failed to regain its traditionally strong showing of support in [[Opinion polling for the next Slovenian parliamentary election|opinion polls]] which had been typical for the party while in opposition. Speaking to the media regarding the faltering performance, SDS officials blamed the government's alleged populist economic policies and a disproportionately hostile news media, while independent political analysts pointed to the [[big tent]] populist appeal of the ruling [[List of Marjan \u0160arec|LM\u0160]] party and [[Marjan \u0160arec|its leader]] that attracted some traditionally conservative voters, and the momentous changes in the political environment and nature of SDS [[Slovenian Democratic Party#2012\u20132013: a year in power (second Jan\u0161a Cabinet)|since 2011-2012]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vecer.com/sds-brez-preboja-za-neuspehe-v-glavnem-krivi-mediji-6656460|title=SDS brez preboja: Za neuspehe v glavnem krivi mediji|date=2019-02-05|website=www.vecer.com|language=sl-si|access-date=2019-02-06}}</ref>\n\n=== 2020\u2013present: third Jan\u0161a Cabinet ===\nIn early 2020, the resignation of the finance minister due to intra-government disagreements regarding the crafting of a health insurance reform bill precipitated the resignation of PM \u0160arec, who called for an early election.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-slovenia-government-idUSKBN1ZQ0RY|title=Slovenian PM Sarec resigns, early election likely|date=2020-01-27|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-03-18|language=en}}</ref> SDS was however able to secure support for the formation of a new SDS-led government by forming a coalition with [[New Slovenia]], [[DeSUS|Democratic Party of Pensioners of Slovenia (DeSUS)]], and [[Modern Centre Party|Modern Centre Party (SMC)]]. While all three parties had expressed clear opposition to a formation of a Jan\u0161a-led government in the past,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mladina.si/182933/koalicija-proti-nestrpnosti/|title=Koalicija proti nestrpnosti|website=Mladina.si|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> all had since experienced changes of leadership that was more amenable to such an arrangement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.primorske.si/2020/02/07/sds-smc-nsi-in-desus-bodo-nadaljevale-pogovore-o-o|title=SDS, SMC, NSi in Desus bodo nadaljevale pogovore o oblikovanju koalicije|last=Krebelj|first=Jana|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mladina.si/195602/pocivalsek-pripravljen-tudi-na-koalicijo-z-janso/|title=Po\u010dival\u0161ek pripravljen tudi na koalicijo z Jan\u0161o|website=Mladina.si|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mladina.si/186504/tonin-se-s-sarcem-ne-bo-vec-pogajal/|title=Tonin se s \u0160arcem ne bo ve\u010d pogajal|website=Mladina.si|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> The news that SMC would be entering into a coalition with Jan\u0161a resulted in the departure of the party's founder and first head, Miro Cerar, after whom the party was initially named (\"Miro Cerar Party\").<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rtvslo.si/slovenija/cerar-izstopil-iz-smc-ja-pocivalsek-iti-moramo-naprej/515953|title=Cerar izstopil iz SMC-ja. Po\u010dival\u0161ek: Iti moramo naprej.|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nJan\u0161a was confirmed as PM on 13 March 2020.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-slovenia-government-idUSKCN20K20B|title=Slovenia president names center-right Janez Jansa as PM candidate|date=2020-02-26|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-03-18|language=en}}</ref> The coalition agreement signed between the 4 parties stipulated, among other things: the re-introduction of the draft and 6 months of mandatory military service, utilisation of private healthcare providers to reduce waiting times, an increase in public and private healthcare funds, promote apprenticeships in vocational school, a commitment to carbon neutrality by 2050, decentralisation, decreasing public spending, an increase in funds for municipalities, tax reductions for performance pay, an increase in pensions, and an introduction of a universal child benefit instead of an income-based one.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vecer.com/kaj-prinasa-koalicijska-pogodba-za-dve-leti-veliko-tople-vode-a-tudi-hladna-prha-10135704|title=Ve\u010der - Kaj prina\u0161a koalicijska pogodba za dve leti? Veliko tople vode, a tudi hladna prha|date=2020-02-29|website=www.vecer.com|language=sl-si|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vecer.com/error404|title=Ve\u010der - error404|website=www.vecer.com|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n\nThe new government took office in the midst of the [[coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://english.sta.si/2739264/jansa-promises-maximum-efforts-to-fight-coronavirus-epidemic|title=STA: Jan\u0161a promises maximum efforts to fight coronavirus epidemic|website=english.sta.si|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> The period during and immediately after the transition of power was marked by a series of controversial actions and decisions by the incoming government. The government allocated the highest possible salaries allowed by law to its ministers and state secretaries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://siol.net/novice/slovenija/ministrom-in-drzavnim-sekretarjem-najvisji-placni-razred-521289|title=Ministrom in dr\u017eavnim sekretarjem v kriznih \u010dasih najvi\u0161ji pla\u010dni razred|website=siol.net|language=sl|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> The state ordered a shipment of surgical masks that failed to arrive. The incident, dubbed \"the Mask Affair\" by the media,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dnevnik.si/1042925194|title=Afera Za\u0161\u010ditne maske: 400.000 evrov mar\u017ee za 3,8 milijona mask|website=Dnevnik|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://necenzurirano.si/clanek/aktualno/dosje-afera-maske-767050|title=(DOSJE) Afera maske|website=Necenzurirano.si|language=sl|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.slovenskenovice.si/novice/slovenija/clanek/afera-zascitne-maske-lastnik-podjetja-razkriva-kaj-se-je-dogajalo-291459|title=Afera za\u0161\u010ditne maske: lastnik podjetja razkriva, kaj se je dogajalo|last=Pa|first=P.|date=2020-03-21|website=www.slovenskenovice.si|language=sl-si|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> led to conflicting statements from two government ministers about whether the order was pre-paid and whether the masks were en-route or actually never existed,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://novice.svet24.si/clanek/novice/slovenija/5e74ef0d6467a/zaplet-z-zascitnimi-maskami-tonin-postavljen-na-laz-podjetje-ki-je-narocilo-maske-potrdilo-pocivalskove-besede|title=Svet24.si - Zaplet z za\u0161\u010ditnimi maskami: Tonin postavljen na la\u017e? Podjetje, ki je naro\u010dilo maske, potrdilo Po\u010dival\u0161kove besede|website=Svet24.si - Vsa resnica na enem mestu|language=sl|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://novice.svet24.si/clanek/novice/slovenija/5e734b5e21523/je-tonin-ze-nasel-izgubljene-maske|title=Svet24.si - Maske ne obstajajo, Tonin je \u010dez no\u010d ugotovil, da je \u0161lo za \"klasi\u010dno prevaro\"|website=Svet24.si - Vsa resnica na enem mestu|language=sl|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref name=\":60\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dnevnik.si/1042925194|title=Afera Za\u0161\u010ditne maske: 400.000 evrov mar\u017ee za 3,8 milijona mask|website=Dnevnik|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> and reports of sketchy busnisses involved in the public procurement process that were anticipating exorbitant profit margins from the deal.<ref name=\":60\" /> A state crisis office was created to confront the epidemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://novice.svet24.si/clanek/novice/slovenija/5e6c8231defb4/krizni-stab-ustanovljen-lahko-recemo-da-je-vrag-se-zdavnaj-odnesel-salo-kot-druzba-se-bomo-morali-korenito-pripraviti-na-spopad-s-to-krizo|title=Svet24.si - Krizni \u0161tab ustanovljen: \"Vrag \u017ee zdavnaj odnesel \u0161alo, kot dru\u017eba se bomo morali korenito pripraviti na spopad s to krizo\"|website=Svet24.si - Vsa resnica na enem mestu|language=sl|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> The official twitter account of the crisis office that was meant to inform te public about the epidemic frequently retweeted articles from SDS's official party newspaper and published an offensive and slanderous statement about four prominent critics of the government (saying that they escaped from a mental hospital and were infected with \"virus COVID-Marx/Lenin\") that prompted a lawsuit against the institution by the subjects of the tweet.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.delo.si/novice/slovenija/tviti-kriznega-staba-takoj-zapadli-politicnemu-obracuvnavanju-289305.html|title=Tviti kriznega \u0161taba takoj zapadli politi\u010dnemu obra\u010dunavanju|last=U|first=V.|date=2020-03-16|website=www.delo.si|language=sl-si|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mladina.si/196960/ovadili-ukinjeni-krizni-stab/|title=Ovadili ukinjeni krizni \u0161tab|website=Mladina.si|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref name=\":61\">{{Cite web|url=https://necenzurirano.si/clanek/aktualno/uradno-nihce-ni-vdrl-v-twitter-kriznega-staba-765083|title=Uradno: nih\u010de ni vdrl v twitter kriznega \u0161taba|website=Necenzurirano.si|language=sl|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> The official explanation for the inappropriate communications - unauthorised access to the account by an unknown individual - was later refuted by the police.<ref name=\":61\" /> The legal basis that would justify the creation of the office was also never explained by the government and the office was subsequently disbanded a mere 9 days after its inception.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dnevnik.si/1042925551|title=Krizni \u0161tab ukinjen, ker se je vlada utekla|website=Dnevnik|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> Upon taking office, the government immediately replaced the leadership of the police, army, and intelligence services. The dismissed general secretary of police<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://novice.svet24.si/clanek/novice/slovenija/5e6c83d6e3645/nova-vlada-nemudoma-zamenjala-vodilne-na-policiji-v-vojski-in-pri-obvescevalcih|title=Svet24.si - Nova vlada nemudoma zamenjala vodilne na policiji, v vojski in pri obve\u0161\u010devalcih|website=Svet24.si - Vsa resnica na enem mestu|language=sl|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> had just recently been admonished by a SDS politician to \"consider her future\" after she refused to make available information during a parliamentary oversight meeting due to a lack of legal authority to do so.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rtvslo.si/slovenija/policija-mahnic-med-preiskavo-pozval-bobnarjevo-naj-pomisli-na-svojo-prihodnost/514834|title=Policija: Mahni\u010d med preiskavo pozval Bobnarjevo, \"naj pomisli na svojo prihodnost\"|website=RTVSLO.si|language=sl|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nThe new government was also keen to replace the head of the National Institute of Public Health (NIJZ). The acting NIJZ director was removed within a weak of the new government taking power, reportedly because she was disfavoured by the PM, and by the new health minister. The government also immediately transferred responsibilities for handling the coronavirus epidemic away from the public health authority and onto the health ministry while SDS-affiliated media disparaged the acting head of NIJZ as inept.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://novice.svet24.si/clanek/novice/slovenija/5e76760e98207/jansev-napad-na-nacionalni-institut-za-javno-zdravje|title=Svet24.si - Jan\u0161ev napad na Nacionalni in\u0161titut za javno zdravje|website=Svet24.si - Vsa resnica na enem mestu|language=sl|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> After the new acting director publically criticised some of the stricter measures intended to combat the epidemic that were enacted by the government as lacking a scientific basis and thus unnecessary,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.24ur.com/novice/slovenija/nijz-razkuzevanje-javnih-povrsin-ni-dolgorocna-resitev.html|title=NIJZ: Razku\u017eevanje javnih povr\u0161in ni dolgoro\u010dna re\u0161itev|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\":63\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.mladina.si/197247/direktor-nijz-meni-da-vladna-zaostritev-ukrepov-za-zajezitev-epidemije-ni-bila-potrebna/|title=Direktor NIJZ meni, da vladna zaostritev ukrepov za zajezitev epidemije ni bila potrebna|website=Mladina.si|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref name=\":64\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.mladina.si/197320/ivan-erzen-po-mojem-mnenju-najnovejsi-drasticni-ukrepi-niso-bili-potrebni-ne-morem-jih-zagovarjat/|title=Ivan Er\u017een: \u00bbPo mojem mnenju najnovej\u0161i drasti\u010dni ukrepi niso bili potrebni. Ne morem jih zagovarjati.\u00ab|website=Mladina.si|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> he too fell out of favour and was rumoured to be up for replacement in short order.<ref name=\":63\" /> Already having replaced one member of the 7-member NIJZ board, the government swiftly replaced the remaining 3 board members of the government 4-member nomination quota, thus gaining a majority capable of appointing a new director. The government had not required a majority to replace the previous director since she resigned voluntarily.<ref name=\":64\" />\n\nAnswering a question about plans for an upcoming gathering of party officials in an interview with [[Dnevnik (Slovenia)|Dnevnik]], soon-to-be PM Jan\u0161a sardonically stated that the party will be discussing the \"editorial policies of Dnevnik\", elaborating with \"Since you're interfering in our party, we shall be interfering with your editorial policies, because we live in a free country.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://zurnal24.si/slovenija/jansa-ze-dokazuje-da-bo-obnovil-stare-prakse-341758|title=Jan\u0161a napovedal vme\u0161avanje v uredni\u0161ko politiko|website=zurnal24.si|language=sl|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> Dnevnik was one of the few media institutions that remained critical of the first Jan\u0161a Cabinet and consequently saw its advertisements from state-owned companies evaporate.<ref name=\":59\" /> In a tweet published shortly after the interview, Jan\u0161a suggested the journalist that conducted the interview may have a drinking problem (Jan\u0161a had also ridiculed the journalist previously).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mladina.si/195989/jansa-bi-se-spet-vmesaval-v-urednisko-politiko-neodvisnih-casopisov/|title=Jan\u0161a bi se spet vme\u0161aval v uredni\u0161ko politiko neodvisnih \u010dasopisov|website=Mladina.si|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> Jan\u0161a was also admonished by the leadership of the public broadcasting institution [[RTV Slovenia]], the Slovenian Union of Journalists, and the Slovene Association of Journalists (DNS) for his attacks on the public broadcaster.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rtvslo.si/slovenija/dns-in-rtv-slo-napadi-na-javni-servis-so-nesprejemljivi/517946|title=DNS in RTV SLO: Napadi na javni servis so nesprejemljivi|website=RTVSLO.si|language=sl|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mladina.si/196896/jansevi-napadi-na-rtv-slovenija-so-nesprejemljivi/|title=Jan\u0161evi napadi na RTV Slovenija so nesprejemljivi|website=Mladina.si|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> A month earlier, DNS had also issued a statement condemning attacks and discreditation of journalists whose reporting was \"uncomfortable for the owners, political allies, and supporters of Slovene media companies with Hungarian ownership\", as these - according to DNS - were intended to discourage such reporting and had come to present a threat to \"journalists, media, and a democratic society\" due to a rise in threats to those journalists from private individuals. DNS had been referring to SDS-aligned media organisations that were financially backed by allies of Hungarian PM [[Viktor Orb\u00e1n|Orb\u00e1n]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mladina.si/195912/napadi-na-novinarje-so-skrajno-nevarni-za-svobodo-izrazanja/|title=Napadi na novinarje so skrajno nevarni za svobodo izra\u017eanja|website=Mladina.si|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> Jan\u0161a also accused RTV SLO of being remiss in their duty to inform the public of the growing threat of global coronavirus contagion in a timely manner.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ostro.si/si/razkrinkavanje/objave/rtv-slovenija-je-pravocasno-opozorila-na-nevarnost-koronavirusa|title=RTV Slovenija je pravo\u010dasno opozorila na nevarnost koronavirusa|website=O\u0161tro|language=sl-SI|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dnevnik.si/1042925377|title=Jan\u0161a krizo izkoristil za napad na RTV Slovenija in direktorja Igorja Kadunca|website=Dnevnik|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> In early April, the government appointed a political ally, Peter Jan\u010di\u010d, to head SiOL, a subsidiary media company owned by the state-owned telecom company, despite receiving the approval of only 2 members of the 42-member editorial board (though only 6 attended, possibly due to the epidemic or in protest over the nomination). Jan\u010di\u010d had previously served as the editor-in-chief of [[Delo (newspaper)|Delo]] (where he had also failed to secure support of the board), and internal politics editor at [[Ve\u010der (Slovenia)|Ve\u010der]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vecer.com/jancic-prevzema-drzavni-siol-brez-vecinske-podpore-novinarjev-10152669|title=Ve\u010der - Jan\u010di\u010d prevzema dr\u017eavni Siol, glasovalo malo novinarjev|date=2020-04-04|website=www.vecer.com|language=sl-si|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref name=\":62\">{{Cite web|url=https://insajder.com/slovenija/peklenski-nacrt-umik-policistov-na-obcinske-meje-janseva-bliznjica-do-uvedbe-neustavnega|title=Peklenski na\u010drt: Umik policistov na ob\u010dinske meje, Jan\u0161eva bli\u017enjica do uvedbe neustavnega izrednega stanja|date=2020-04-05|website=Insajder.com - Objektivno. Odkrito. To\u010dno.|language=sl|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> Immediately upon taking the position of the editor-in-chief, Jan\u010di\u010d penned an op-ed praising the new government, critiquing the opposition, and slamming a columnist and co-worker.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://siol.net/siol-plus/kolumne/svoboda-sarca-in-janse-522464|title=Svoboda \u0160arca in Jan\u0161e|website=siol.net|language=sl|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref name=\":62\" />\n\n== Ideology ==\n=== Populism ===\nDuring the [[European migrant crisis]], SDS sharply intensified its nationalist populist rhetoric.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/jun/01/drain-the-swamp-rightwing-leader-pulls-ahead-in-slovenias-polls|title='Drain the swamp': rightwing leader pulls ahead in Slovenia's polls|last=MacDowall|first=Andrew|date=2018-06-01|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-06-02}}</ref><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.euronews.com/2018/06/01/explained-slovenia-s-elections-and-orban-s-populist-influence|title=Explained: Slovenia's election and Orban's populist influence|date=2018-06-01|work=euronews|access-date=2018-06-02|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/03/world/europe/slovenia-election.html|title=Slovenia Elections Tilt Another European Country to the Right|date=2018-06-03|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-06-04|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The party came out in opposition of migrant quotas and advocated shifting resources from non-governmental organisations to increase security spending.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-slovenia-election/anti-immigrant-stance-helps-slovenias-sds-party-to-poll-lead-idUSKCN1IN1QU|title=Anti-immigrant stance helps Slovenia's SDS party to poll lead|last=Novak|first=Marja|work=U.S.|access-date=2018-06-02|language=en-US}}</ref> Jan\u0161a furthermore lambasted the \"degenerate left\".<ref name=\":8\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dw.comhttp//www.dw.com/en/orban-ally-janez-jansa-expected-to-top-slovenias-election/a-44055791-0|title=Orban ally Janez Jansa expected to top Slovenia's election {{!}} DW {{!}} 02.06.2018|last=Welle (www.dw.com)|first=Deutsche|website=DW.COM|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-07-20}}</ref> The party's heated rhetoric and allegations of corrupt practices have led \"to concerns among international observers about the direction of Slovenia, which is generally regarded as a regional success story\" as SDS topped [[Opinion polling for the Slovenian parliamentary election, 2018|opinion polls]] heading into the 2018 parliamentary election.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\nThe party has also co-opted US President Donald Trump's populist rhetoric,<ref name=\":30\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.delo.si/sobotna/najprej-slovenija-kaj-pa-potem.html|title=Najprej Slovenija. Kaj pa potem?|last=Marke\u0161|first=Janez|access-date=2018-06-05|language=sl-si}}</ref> with Jan\u0161a and the party frequently echoing Trump's catchphrases \"drain the swamp\",<ref name=\":8\"/> \"deep state\",<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.demokracija.si/komentar/ali-v-sloveniji-obstaja-globoka-drzava.html|title=Ali v Sloveniji obstaja globoka dr\u017eava?|last=Umek|first=prof. dr. Andrej|access-date=2018-06-04|language=sl-si}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mladina.si/45132/globoka-drzava/|title=Globoka dr\u017eava|work=Mladina.si|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref> and \"fake news\".<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/slovenian-survivor-targets-victory-a-la-orban/|title=Slovenian survivor targets victory \u00e0 la Orb\u00e1n|date=2018-06-01|work=POLITICO|access-date=2018-06-02|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\":31\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.dw.com/en/orban-ally-janez-jansa-expected-to-top-slovenias-election/a-44055791|title=Orban ally Janez Jansa expected to top Slovenia's election {{!}} DW {{!}} 02.06.2018|last=(www.dw.com)|first=Deutsche Welle|website=DW.COM|language=en|access-date=2018-06-05}}</ref> The party has also proposed requiring that for each new regulation, two existing regulations must be repealed,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sds.si/novica/janez-jansa-za-vsak-nov-predpis-naj-se-dva-ukine-13794|title=Janez Jan\u0161a: Za vsak nov predpis naj se dva ukine! {{!}} SDS|website=www.sds.si|language=sl|access-date=2018-06-02}}</ref> a proposal notably advocated for and enacted by Trump.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/business/archive/2017/01/trumps-regulation-eo/515007/|title=Trump's 'Two-for-One' Regulation Executive Order|last=Lam|first=Bourree|date=2017-01-30|work=The Atlantic|access-date=2018-06-02|language=en-US}}</ref> Jan\u0161a has also used the phrase \"Slovenia first\" on several occasions.<ref name=\":32\" /><ref name=\":30\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rtvslo.si/slovenija/jansa-najprej-slovenija-potem-drugi/446321|title=Jan\u0161a: Najprej Slovenija, potem drugi|work=Prvi interaktivni multimedijski portal, MMC RTV Slovenija|access-date=2018-06-07}}</ref><ref name=\":43\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.total-slovenia-news.com/politics/1045-elections-2018-party-profiles-sds-the-janez-jansa-party-feature|title=Elections 2018, Party Profiles: SDS, the Janez Jan\u0161a Party (Feature)|access-date=2018-07-03|language=en-gb}}</ref>\n\n=== Domestic policy ===\n==== Economic policy ====\nSDS has been described as broadly pro-market,<ref name=\":25\" /> and its economic policies have been characterised as [[Neoliberalism|neoliberal]].<ref name=\":43\" /> SDS advocates for lower taxes and speeding up privatisation efforts.<ref name=\":32\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/jun/03/anti-immigration-party-leads-exit-poll-in-slovenian-election|title=Slovenian nationalist party set for power after winning election|last=Agencies|date=2018-06-04|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-06-05}}</ref>\n\n==== Social policy ====\nSDS introduced legislation allowing for same-sex civil unions while in government,<ref name=\":25\" /> but has opposed recognition of same-sex marriages.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-slovenia-rights/slovenia-rejects-same-sex-marriages-in-a-referendum-idUSKBN0U30BS20151220|title=Slovenia rejects same-sex marriages in a referendum|last=Novak|first=Marja|work=U.S.|access-date=2018-06-05|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/22/world/europe/slovenians-deliver-major-setback-to-same-sex-marriage-in-vote.html|title=Slovenians Deliver Major Setback to Same-Sex Marriage in Referendum|date=2015-12-21|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-06-05|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==== Education policy ====\nSDS advocates for the introduction of educational programs that would foster patriotism \"from kindergarten through high school\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.delo.si/novice/politika/tudi-sds-za-domoljubno-vzgojo-od-vrtca-do-srednje-sole.html|title=Tudi SDS za domoljubno vzgojo od vrtca do srednje \u0161ole|last=STA|first=Pi. K., Delo.si|access-date=2018-06-07|language=sl-si}}</ref> The party supports full public financing of private school compulsory programs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://english.sta.si/2477065/sds-proposal-for-full-funding-of-private-schools-rejected|title=STA: SDS proposal for full funding of private schools rejected|website=english.sta.si|language=en|access-date=2018-06-07}}</ref>\n\n==== National security ====\nJan\u0161a has expressed strong support for the re-enstatement of [[mandatory military service]] for males with service lasting at least 6 months.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://zurnal24.si/slovenija/jansa-spet-je-treba-uvesti-obvezni-vojaski-rok-339974|title=Jan\u0161a: Spet je treba uvesti obvezni voja\u0161ki rok|website=zurnal24.si|language=sl|access-date=2020-01-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sds.si/novica/v-sds-predlagamo-ponovno-uvedbo-nabornistva-v-obliki-sluzenja-6-mesecnega-vojaskega-roka|title=V SDS predlagamo ponovno uvedbo naborni\u0161tva v obliki slu\u017eenja 6-mese\u010dnega voja\u0161kega roka|website=www.sds.si|language=sl|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> In early 2016, SDS proposed the establishment of a national guard composed of some 25,000 \"patriotic\" volunteers. The guard would replace all current reserve formations of the Slovene armed forces, would be under direct command of the general staff, and would be mobilised during natural disasters or during \"altered national security states\" (like the European refugee crisis, which was ongoing at the time). Both sexes could enlist. MP \u017dan Mahni\u010d stated the establishment of the formation was a priority of the party's electoral platform. The proposal was prompted by worsening global national security prospects, in part due to the migrant crisis, a SDS representative said.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rtvslo.si/slovenija/sds-bi-25-000-domoljubov-zdruzil-v-nacionalni-gardi/383775|title=SDS bi 25.000 domoljubov zdru\u017eil v nacionalni gardi|work=Prvi interaktivni multimedijski portal, MMC RTV Slovenija|access-date=2018-06-07}}</ref> Government representatives argued that such a formation is unnecessary as the current reserve formations are sufficient.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rtvslo.si/slovenija/zl-nacionalno-gardo-vidi-kot-desnicarsko-paravojsko-nsi-idejo-podpira/383871|title=ZL nacionalno gardo vidi kot \"desni\u010darsko paravojsko\", NSi idejo podpira|work=Prvi interaktivni multimedijski portal, MMC RTV Slovenija|access-date=2018-06-07}}</ref>\n\n==== Judiciary and law enforcement ====\nSDS advocates for trials to be open to the public (except in special circumstances).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sds.si/zate/program|title=Program ZATE - Za pravi\u010dno sojenje {{!}} SDS|website=www.sds.si|language=sl|access-date=2018-06-10}}</ref>\n\n==== Environment and climate change ====\nDuring the first SDS government, PM Jan\u0161a presented climate change as the major political and societal challenge of the era. In 2007, Jan\u0161a stated that \"climate change is not only a problem for the government and economy; it is a challenge for the wider society and every individual\" during an international conference on the matter, stressing the dangers and opportunities associated with the issue. He called on the EU to lead the efforts to combat climate change.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nekdanji-pv.gov.si/2004-2008/nc/en/splosno/cns/news/article/252/2276/index.html|title=Prime Minister Janez Jan\u0161a: Climate change is a challenge for the wider society and every individual|website=www.nekdanji-pv.gov.si|access-date=2019-08-07}}</ref> In 2008, Jan\u0161a described an EU legislative package on energy and climate change as \"one of the most important [...] of the beginning of the 21st century\", and as one of the priorities of Slovenia during its EU Council Presidency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nekdanji-pv.gov.si/2004-2008/nc/en/splosno/cns/news/article/1914/2514/index.html|title=Prime Minister Janez Jan\u0161a: The legislative package on energy and climate change is one of the most important legislative packages of the beginning of the 21st century|website=www.nekdanji-pv.gov.si|access-date=2019-08-07}}</ref> In 2008, SDS MEP [[Romana Jordan Cizelj]] stated that \"counteracting climate change is not an individual choice, but a global challenge requiring the effort of the society as a whole. [...] The data reveal changes in ecosystems due to antropogenic emissions and possible trends in the future. [...] It is still possible to act. But we must act decisively, swiftly, and in unison. First in coordination within the EU, and then in the global sense.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sds.si/novica/dr-romana-jordan-cizelj-o-podnebnih-spremembah-6825|title=Dr. Romana Jordan Cizelj o podnebnih spremembah|website=www.sds.si|language=sl|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref>\n\nBy 2018, the party seemed to have reversed its position on the issue, with MP Branko Grims prominently making multiple public statements, including in media statements and parliamentary discussions, that outright denied the existence of anthropogenic climate change.<ref name=\"nova24tv.si\">{{Cite web|url=https://nova24tv.si/slovenija/politika/lposlanec-grims-odgovarja-ekosocialistom-ekologija-je-200-milijard-vreden-posel-lobijev-povezanih-z-levicarji/|title=[Video] Poslanec Grims odgovarja ekosocialistom: Ekolo\u0161ki davki se ne porabljajo namensko, temve\u010d gredo v \u017eepe levi\u010darjev!|date=2018-12-29|website=Nova24TV|language=sl-SI|access-date=2019-08-07}}</ref><ref name=\":26\">{{Cite web|url=https://siol.net/novice/slovenija/grims-trdi-eno-znanstveniki-se-z-njim-ne-strinjajo-485389|title=Grims trdi eno, znanstveniki se z njim ne strinjajo|website=siol.net|language=sl|access-date=2019-08-07}}</ref><ref name=\":44\">{{Cite web|url=https://novice.svet24.si/clanek/novice/slovenija/5c408fbfd8255/globalno-segrevanje-ne-obstaja-to-je-larifari|title=Svet24.si - Branko Grims: \"Globalno segrevanje ne obstaja. To je larifari\"|website=Svet24.si - Vsa resnica na enem mestu|language=sl|access-date=2019-08-07}}</ref> Grims has said that \"the talk about the warming of the Earth is a [[big lie]]\", that the Earth is in fact cooling,<ref name=\":26\" /> that climate change is being used as an excuse to allow for mass migrations and the expropriation of taxpayer funds<ref name=\":44\" /> that are then embezzled by academics, the \"eco-industry\" and leftist lobbies,<ref name=\"nova24tv.si\"/><ref name=\":56\">{{Cite web|url=https://nova24tv.si/slovenija/politika/video-grims-razkrinkal-levicarsko-pranje-mozganov-s-podnebnimi-spremembami-na-racun-katerih-lahko-nevladniki-zasluzijo-tudi-prek-20-000-evrov-mesecno/|title=[Video] Grims razkrinkal levi\u010darsko pranje mo\u017eganov s podnebnimi spremembami, na ra\u010dun katerih lahko nevladniki zaslu\u017eijo tudi prek 20 tiso\u010d evrov mese\u010dno!|date=2019-03-25|website=Nova24TV|language=sl-SI|access-date=2019-08-07}}</ref> and expressed regret that [[School strike for climate|the youth]] were being exploited by the political left.<ref name=\":56\" /> Grims has appealed to his background as a geologist to present himself as authoritative on the issue.<ref name=\":26\" /> Grims also controversially claimed that the black panther, which is ostensibly represented in the [[Carantania]]n panther sigil that has been adopted as the alternate national symbol by some modern-era conservative political groups,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.24ur.com/novice/slovenija/od-kje-se-je-vzel-panter-s-katerim-je-sisko-zamenjal-triglav.html|title=Od kod se je 'vzel' panter, s katerim je \u0160i\u0161ko zamenjal Triglav?|website=www.24ur.com|access-date=2019-08-07}}</ref> was native to the Slovene region but became extinct due to global cooling during the Carantanian era. Experts, commenting on Grims' statement, said that the black panther has not been endemic to the region since at least the most recent ice age.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.24ur.com/branko-grims-govorjenje-o-segrevanju-zemlje-je-velika-laz.html|title=Branko Grims: 'Govorjenje o segrevanju zemlje je velika la\u017e'|website=www.24ur.com|access-date=2019-08-07}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, Jan\u0161a, discussing climate change, stated: \"[...] Times are different now, generations are growing up with an awareness that the environment is a value. Of course, some on the left scene pervaded by [[cultural Marxism]] have swiftly added catastrofic proclamations which are supposed to be caused by climate change. It is being preached how climate change is exclusively man-made, which is entirely unproven. Climate change has been occurring throughout the history of this planet and will continue to. To what extent we are influencing this is a big question. It is a fact that we are. It is a fact that environmental pollution of course in part affects the climate. But I think that it affects it much less than changes on the Sun, or, that is, things which humans cannot influence. This must be understood and it should not be made into ideology and the fame of new [[Moloch|Molochs]], such as [[Greta Thunberg|Greta]].\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.demokracija.si/fokus/janez-jansa-to-je-globoka-drzava-to-ni-politicna-tvorba-to-je-mafija.html|title=Janez Jan\u0161a: To je globoka dr\u017eava. To ni politi\u010dna tvorba. To je mafija.|last=nova24tv.si|first=vir|website=www.demokracija.si|language=sl-si|access-date=2019-11-27}}</ref>\n\n==== Other policies ====\nSDS has long advocated for a change in the Slovene parliamentary electoral system, namely the shift from the current [[proportional electoral system]] to two-round [[plurality voting]]. SDS argues this would result in more stable and effective governments.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sds.si/en/about-sds/programme|title=About SDS - Programme {{!}} SDS|website=www.sds.si|language=en|access-date=2018-06-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dnevnik.si/1042573817|title=Za SDS ve\u010dinski volilni sistem re\u0161itev vseh te\u017eav|work=Dnevnik|access-date=2018-06-10}}</ref>\n\nSDS supports citizens' legal right to bear arms, and has come out in opposition to further restrictions. It strongly opposed new EU regulation of firearms which the European Commission moved to pass after the [[November 2015 Paris attacks|2015 Paris terrorist attacks]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.domovina.je/sds-proti-predlogu-za-otezitev-dostopa-do-orozja/|title=SDS proti predlogu za ote\u017eitev dostopa do oro\u017eja {{!}} Domovina|last=Uredni\u0161tvo|website=www.domovina.je|language=sl-SI|access-date=2018-06-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sta.si/2215016/sds-zaradi-predloga-za-otezitev-dostopa-do-orozja-za-izredno-sejo-odbora-dz|title=STA: SDS zaradi predloga za ote\u017eitev dostopa do oro\u017eja za izredno sejo odbora DZ|website=www.sta.si|language=sl|access-date=2018-06-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rtvslo.si/evropska-unija/evroposlanci-sprejeli-strozjo-zakonodajo-o-orozju/417322|title=Evroposlanci sprejeli stro\u017ejo zakonodajo o oro\u017eju|work=Prvi interaktivni multimedijski portal, MMC RTV Slovenija|access-date=2018-06-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mladina.si/171786/ljudska-obramba/|title=Ljudska obramba|work=Mladina.si|access-date=2018-06-07}}</ref>\n\nSDS argues the current text to the [[Anthem of the Slovene nation|Slovene national anthem]]\u2014the 7th stanza of [[France Pre\u0161eren|France Pre\u0161eren's]] [[Zdravljica|A Toast]] (\"Blessed be all nations/Which yearn to see the light of day/When where'er the Sun doth wander/The lands' strife shall be cast away/And when free every kinsman will be/Not fiends, only neighbours in foreigners we'll see!\")\u2014is \"too internationalistic, and insufficiently patriotic\", and advocates other stanzas from Pre\u0161eren's poem be added as text to the official anthem.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rtvslo.si/slovenija/kot-himno-bomo-se-peli-7-kitico-presernove-zdravljice/259929|title=Kot himno bomo \u0161e peli 7. kitico Pre\u0161ernove Zdravljice|work=Prvi interaktivni multimedijski portal, MMC RTV Slovenija|access-date=2018-06-21}}</ref><ref name=\":40\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.rtvslo.si/slovenija/retroaktivnost-v-predlogu-sds-a-o-nezastarljivosti-umora-neustavna/331314|title=Retroaktivnost v predlogu SDS-a o nezastarljivosti umora \"neustavna\"|work=Prvi interaktivni multimedijski portal, MMC RTV Slovenija|access-date=2018-06-21}}</ref><ref name=\":41\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.delo.si/novice/politika/poslanci-nasprotujejo-spremembam-zakona-o-drzavnih-simbolih.html|title=SDS znova neuspe\u0161na s predlogom zakona o dr\u017eavnih simbolih|last=STA|first=Ni. \u010c., Delo.si|access-date=2018-06-21|language=sl-si}}</ref> The party also advocates banning \"all public expression of ideas through use of totalitarian symbols\" and \"all public displays of affection for totalitarian regimes\".<ref name=\":40\" /><ref name=\":41\" /> The party has denied accusations that it is merely attempting to outlaw the [[red star]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rtvslo.si/slovenija/rdeca-zvezda-in-himna-ostajata-glasbene-kvote-ne-bodo-zvisane/356835|title=Rde\u010da zvezda in himna ostajata, glasbene kvote ne bodo zvi\u0161ane|work=Prvi interaktivni multimedijski portal, MMC RTV Slovenija|access-date=2018-06-21}}</ref> which was the symbol of the [[Slovene Partisans]] during WWII,<ref name=\":42\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.mladina.si/153846/prepoved-rdece-zvezde/|title=Prepoved rde\u010de zvezde|work=Mladina.si|access-date=2018-06-21}}</ref> and is still often used in the Slovenian public sphere,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dnevnik.si/1042595774|title=Rde\u010da zvezda je spet razdvajala (foto)|work=Dnevnik|access-date=2018-06-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.delo.si/lokalno/ljubljana-in-okolica/dan-ko-je-sijala-rdeca-zvezda-54072.html|title=FOTO:Dan, ko je sijala rde\u010da zvezda|last=R.|first=Z.|access-date=2018-06-21|language=sl-si}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.primorske.si/slovenija/nosil-bom-rdeco-zvezdo-s-svetlano-makarovic-na-cel|title=Nosil bom rde\u010do zvezdo s Svetlano Makarovi\u010d na \u010delu ponovno na Kongresnem trgu}}</ref> including as a symbol/logo of political and [[The Left (Slovenia)|parliamentary parties]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dsd.si/|title=Vstopna|website=Zdru\u017eena levica - Demokrati\u010dna stranka dela {{!}} ZL-DSD|language=sl-SI|access-date=2018-06-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dnevnik.si/1042776276|title=Pod rde\u010do zvezdo rojena Levica ne bo ve\u010dna opozicija|work=Dnevnik|access-date=2018-06-21}}</ref> The proposed law would not, on the other hand, ban wearing Nazi uniforms in public or displaying symbols associated with the Nazi-aligned anti-Partisan [[Slovene Home Guard]].<ref name=\":42\" />\n\n=== Foreign policy ===\nThe party is pro-European,<ref name=\":25\" /> but staunchly anti-immigration and strongly opposed to EU asylum quotas.<ref name=\":32\" /> The party is committed to Slovenia's continuing membership in NATO.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sds.si/program|title=Program|website=www.sds.si|language=sl|access-date=2020-01-12}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the US targeted killing of Iranian gen. [[Qasem Soleimani]], the party released a statement declaring that \"SDS supports the strong US response to the provocations of the Ayatollah extremist regime [...]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sds.si/en/novica/slovenian-democratic-party-sds-condemns-unreasonable-support-of-leftist-slovenian-1|title=Slovenian Democratic Party (SDS) condemns unreasonable support of leftist Slovenian political forces to the Iranian regime|website=www.sds.si|language=en|access-date=2020-01-12}}</ref>\n\n=== Post-communist cabal conspiracy ===\nPerhaps the most peculiar aspect of SDS ideology are the unique beliefs and rhetoric frequently employed by members of the party. The central tenet of the party's view regarding the country's political situation is that a sinister clique composed mostly of leftist former communist party officials has retained significant control over the economic, financial, political, social, judicial, and journalistic aspects of Slovenian public life. Some of the beliefs and language used are also shared by other right-wing populist political actors, or have entered into the mainstream political discourse.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://english.sta.si/2245524/slovenian-political-metaphors-and-metonymy-a-guide|title=STA: Slovenian political metaphors and metonymy - a guide|website=english.sta.si|language=en|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref><ref name=\":33\" /><ref name=\":39\" /><ref name=\":43\" />{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\nSDS members and affiliates frequently employ particular phrases and concepts to represent their world-view, most notably:\n* \"Udbomafia\" (from [[UDBA]], the Yugoslav secret police service) \u2013 a portmanteau neologism coined in the early 1990s to refer to an alleged cabal of former [[League of Communists of Slovenia|Slovenian Communist Party]] members, and UDBA informants and collaborators that supposedly still hold the reins of economic and political control. The phrase is often used by SDS and affiliated publications.<ref name=\":33\">{{Cite news|url=http://nova24tv.si/news/have-you-heard-of-kucans-clan-a-mafia-like-group-from-the-league-of-communists-whose-aim-was-to-economically-control-slovenia-after-its-independence-and-assure-the-survival-of-thei/|title=Have you heard of Ku\u010dan's clan \u2013 a mafia-like group from the League of Communists, whose aim was to economically control Slovenia after its independence and assure the survival of their children? {{!}} Nova24TV|date=2017-12-19|work=Nova24TV|access-date=2018-06-05|language=sl-SI}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=bNvbHCUs3tUC&pg=PA213&dq=udbomafia#v=onepage&q=udbomafia&f=false|title=Politics, Power and the Struggle for Democracy in South-East Europe|last=Dawisha|first=Karen|last2=Parrott|first2=Bruce|date=1997-06-13|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9780521597333|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=l-T1dAxBkHUC&pg=PA314&dq=udbomafia#v=onepage&q=udbomafia&f=false|title=New Xenophobia in Europe|last=Baumgartl|first=Bernd|last2=Favell|first2=Adrian|date=1995-10-02|publisher=Martinus Nijhoff Publishers|isbn=9041108653|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=QZr1vsDIvlUC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA159#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Radical Right in Central and Eastern Europe Since 1989|last=Ramet|first=Sabrina P.|date=2010-11-01|publisher=Penn State Press|isbn=978-0271043791|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mladina.si/?__rewriter=1&id=147621&|title=Nadaljnje delitve naroda na rde\u010de in \u010drne|work=Mladina.si|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://english.sta.si/2186108/demokracija-smells-corruption-in-bad-bank-dismissals|title=STA: Demokracija \"smells corruption\" in bad bank dismissals|website=english.sta.si|language=en|access-date=2018-06-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://english.sta.si/2428011/weekly-parties-might-have-been-bribed-in-iran-money-laundering|title=STA: Weekly: Parties might have been bribed in Iran money laundering|website=english.sta.si|language=en|access-date=2018-06-05}}</ref>\n* \"Uncles from behind the scenes\" (or \"godfathers in the background,\" an idiom for [[\u00e9minence grise]]) \u2013 alleged sponsors and influencers of prominent Slovene politicians who are said to merely act as fronts for the vested political and economic interests of the \"uncles\". Former PMs [[Miro Cerar]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://english.sta.si/2506893/reporter-takes-a-swing-at-cerar|title=STA: Reporter takes a swing at Cerar|website=english.sta.si|language=en|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref> and Alenka Bratu\u0161ek,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://reporter.si/clanek/slovenija/jerajeva-bratuskova-se-ves-cas-posvetuje-s-strici-iz-ozadja-445618|title=Jerajeva: Bratu\u0161kova se ves \u010das posvetuje s strici iz ozadja {{!}} Revija Reporter|website=Revija Reporter|language=sl-SI|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref> PS head Zoran Jankovi\u0107,<ref name=\"auto4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.mladina.si/107642/strici-iz-ozadja/|title=Strici iz ozadja|work=Mladina.si|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref> and anti-establishment newcomer [[Marjan \u0160arec]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://english.sta.si/2507852/demokracija-identifies-little-uncle-behind-sarec|title=STA: Demokracija identifies \"little uncle\" behind \u0160arec|website=english.sta.si|language=en|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref> are some of the politicians accused of having \"uncles from behind the scenes\". The phrase was also occasionally used by former PM and President [[Borut Pahor]], on one occasion accusing the \"uncles\" of attempting to topple his premiership.<ref name=\":27\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.rtvslo.si/svet/svetovni-mediji-o-pahorjevem-politicnem-hat-tricku-v-senci-ljudske-vstaje/297189|title=Svetovni mediji o Pahorjevem \"politi\u010dnem hat-tricku\" v senci ljudske vstaje|work=Prvi interaktivni multimedijski portal, MMC RTV Slovenija|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref><ref name=\":27\" /> Milan Ku\u010dan, who is most often accused of being the foremost \"uncle from behind the scenes\", demanded Pahor clarify his insinuation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dnevnik.si/1042564708|title=Svet iz ozadja ali politi\u010dna paranoja?|work=Dnevnik|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref> Pahor also accused his main [[2017 Slovenian presidential election|2017 presidential election]] challenger, Marjan \u0160arec, of being well looked after by the \"uncles\". \u0160arec likewise demanded Pahor clarify his statements, but also did not receive an answer.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.zurnal24.si/slovenija/ne-skrbite-strici-iz-ozadja-skrbijo-za-vas-299661|title=Ne skrbite, strici iz ozadja skrbijo za vas|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=2018-06-04|language=sl}}</ref>\n* [[Milan Ku\u010dan]] \u2013 the former two-time President of Slovenia and last leader of the [[League of Communists of Slovenia]] is frequently accused by SDS of exerting supreme covert influence over the Slovenian political sphere.<ref name=\":43\" /><ref name=\":33\" /><ref name=\":23\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.sloveniatimes.com/jansa-to-fight-to-the-end-says-conviction-political|title=Jan\u0161a to \"Fight to the End\", Says Conviction Political|website=www.sloveniatimes.com|language=sl|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref><ref name=\":24\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.mladina.si/166015/milan-kucan/|title=Milan Ku\u010dan|work=Mladina.si|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.politikis.si/2012/03/kucanu-razpada-njegov-forum-21-kosarico-mu-je-ze-dala-tudi-pergarjeva/|title=Ku\u010danu razpada njegov Forum 21, ko\u0161arico mu je \u017ee dala tudi Pergarjeva! {{!}} Politikis|website=www.politikis.si|language=sl-SI|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref> Politicians allegedly under Ku\u010dan's influence include [[New Slovenia]] leader [[Ljudmila Novak]] and 2018 newcomer Marjan \u0160arec,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nova24tv.si/slovenija/kucan-je-spoznal-da-sarec-ne-more-zmagati-zdaj-vse-orozje-polaga-v-ljudmilo-novak-ki-naj-bi-razklala-desnico/|title=Ku\u010dan je spoznal, da \u0160arec ne more zmagati \u2013 zdaj vse oro\u017eje polaga v Ljudmilo Novak, ki naj bi \"razklala\" desnico {{!}} Nova24TV|date=2017-08-21|work=Nova24TV|access-date=2018-06-04|language=sl-SI}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vinkogorenak.net/2017/11/13/milan-kucan-marjan-sarec-in-jaka-racman/|title=Milan Ku\u010dan, Marjan \u0160arec in Jaka Racman \u2013 dr. Vinko Gorenak|website=www.vinkogorenak.net|language=sl-SI|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref> former PM [[Alenka Bratu\u0161ek]] and Ljubljana mayor and PS leader [[Zoran Jankovi\u0107 (politician)|Zoran Jankovi\u0107]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sloveniatimes.com/jansa-sent-to-prison-he-is-convinced-that-everything-is-political-plot|title=Jan\u0161a Sent to Prison, He is Convinced About Political Plot|website=www.sloveniatimes.com|language=sl|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref><ref name=\"auto4\"/> and others. Jan\u0161a was fined \u20ac12,000 after labelling two female RTV Slovenia journalists as \"cheap, used-up prostitutes\" of \"#pimpMilan\" [Ku\u010dan] in a tweet,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vecer.com/jansa-ni-priznal-krivde-zaradi-zaljivega-tvita-o-novinarkah-rtvs-6257118|title=Jan\u0161a ni priznal krivde zaradi \u017ealjivega tvita o novinarkah RTVS|work=\u010casnik Ve\u010der d.o.o.|access-date=2018-06-04|language=sl-si}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://english.sta.si/2245522/more-condemnation-of-jansas-defamatory-tweet|title=STA: More condemnation of Jan\u0161a's defamatory tweet|website=english.sta.si|language=en|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://english.sta.si/2245794/insulting-tweet-labelled-as-attack-on-media|title=STA: Insulting tweet labelled as attack on media|website=english.sta.si|language=en|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref> later also receiving a 3-month suspended jail sentence for the offense.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-xl/europe/top-stories/slovenia-right-wing-politician-gets-3-month-suspended-jail/ar-BBQ2xR9|title=Slovenia right-wing politician gets 3-month suspended jail|website=www.msn.com|language=en-XL|access-date=2018-11-25}}</ref>\n* Forum 21 \u2013 a Slovenian liberal think tank established by Milan Ku\u010dan and attended by prominent members of the Slovenian political and economic elite to discuss relevant problems facing the nation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.forum21.si/o-nas.html|title=O nas {{!}} Forum21|last=d.o.o.|first=PGMPRO|website=www.forum21.si|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mladina.si/92481/kdo-vozi-forum-21/|title=Kdo vozi forum 21?|work=Mladina.si|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref><ref name=\":24\" /> SDS has accused the think tank of undue influence in appointment and policy decisions of liberal governments.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://siol.net/novice/slovenija/sds-kadroval-bo-forum-21-122075|title=SDS: Kadroval bo Forum 21|access-date=2018-06-04|language=sl}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.finance.si/267592/Odmev-Srotova-tajkunska-botra-sta-SD-in-Forum-21|title=Odmev: \u0160rotova tajkunska botra sta SD in Forum 21|work=Finance.si|access-date=2018-06-04|language=sl-SI}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dnevnik.si/1042772947|title=Milan Ku\u010dan: Drugi tir ni projekt Foruma 21|work=Dnevnik|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref>\n* Murgle \u2013 the upscale Murgle residential district known for its one-story houses is home to many prominent Slovenian political and economic figures, including former liberal presidents Milan Ku\u010dan (often the main target of allusions to \"Murgle\") and [[Janez Drnov\u0161ek]] (deceased), former PM [[Miro Cerar]], and Liberation Front partisan and last president of the [[Socialist Republic of Slovenia|SR Slovenia]], [[Janez Stanovnik]], among others.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.times.si/slovenija/foto-to-so-hise-murgelske-elite--513e3dc006e6293b7a62f8e1a1030fd11d0c4395.html|title=FOTO: To so hi\u0161e murgelske elite|work=Times.si|access-date=2018-06-04|language=sl}}</ref> \"Murgle\" is thus another reference to the alleged behind-the-scenes influence exerted by the country's ostensibly retired leftist elites. Upon being sentenced to a two-year prison sentence in the [[Patria case|Patria corruption case]], Janez Jan\u0161a stated that the verdict was \"written in advance in Murgle and by known authors\".<ref name=\":23\" /> SDS later labelled the 2014 parliamentary election as illegitimate due to the conviction and resulting concurring prison term of Jan\u0161a.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rtvslo.si/slovenija/podrzaj-jansa-je-sluzbo-dobil-na-volitvah-zakon-mu-udelezbe-ne-preprecuje/343080|title=Podr\u017eaj: Jan\u0161a je slu\u017ebo dobil na volitvah, zakon mu udele\u017ebe ne prepre\u010duje|work=Prvi interaktivni multimedijski portal, MMC RTV Slovenija|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.24ur.com/novice/slovenija/zapornik-jansa-prihaja-v-parlament.html|title=Jan\u0161a bo lahko brez spremstva zapustil zapor in se udele\u017eil ustanovne seje|website=www.24ur.com|language=sl|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref><ref name=\":29\">{{Cite news|url=https://siol.net/novice/slovenija/sds-poziva-pahorja-naj-ponovno-razpise-volitve-foto-249460|title=SDS poziva Pahorja, naj ponovno razpi\u0161e volitve (foto)|access-date=2018-06-04|language=sl}}</ref> Jan\u0161a also blamed \"Murgle\" after prosecutors filed a motion to confiscate Jan\u0161a's illegally obtained holdings.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.zurnal24.si/slovenija/jansa-volitve-so-blizu-in-murgle-spet-udarjajo-z-repom-289338|title=Jan\u0161a: Volitve so blizu in Murgle spet udarjajo z repom|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=2018-06-04|language=sl}}</ref> As part of its 2018 electoral campaign, SDS released an ad where a couple orders pizza delivery from SDS and \"Pizza Murgle\". The Murgle box is revealed to only contain half a pizza.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/slovenian-survivor-targets-victory-a-la-orban/|title=Slovenian survivor targets victory \u00e0 la Orb\u00e1n|date=2018-06-01|work=POLITICO|access-date=2018-06-04|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=SDS TV|title=Ne dovolite, da vas zavedejo z lepimi besedami. Premislite, preden izberete! #SDSzate|date=2018-05-25|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VaNDNPOIuus|accessdate=2018-06-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://vezjak.com/2018/05/25/murgelska-pica-ali-jansa-v-piceriji/|title=Murgelska pica ali SDS v piceriji|date=2018-05-25|work=::: IN MEDIA RES|access-date=2018-06-04|language=sl-SI}}</ref> SDS-affiliated<ref name=\":34\" /> Nova24TV news portal also promoted videos entitled \"Murgle Puppet Theatre\", which satirically portrayed a closed-door meeting presided over by Milan Ku\u010dan discussing political strategy with recently resigned PM Miro Cerar (leader of ruling [[Modern Centre Party]]), Agriculture Minister [[Dejan \u017didan]] (leader of the [[Social Democrats (Slovenia)|Social Democrats]]), Foreign Minister [[Karl Erjavec]] (leader of [[DeSUS]]), and [[Marjan \u0160arec]] (leader of the [[List of Marjan \u0160arec]]).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nova24tv.si/sprosceno/gledalisce-murgle-1-del-kucan-zidan-cerar-erjavec-in-sarec-o-sanaciji-bank-z-iranci-palestinci-in-sirci/|title=Gledali\u0161\u010de Murgle 1. del: Ku\u010dan, \u017didan, Cerar, Erjavec in \u0160arec o sanaciji bank z Iranci, Palestinci in Sirci|date=2018-05-28|work=Nova24TV|access-date=2018-06-04|language=sl-SI}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nova24tv.si/sprosceno/gledalisce-murgle-2-del-uvaza-se-veliko-migrantov-izvaza-veliko-izobrazenih-ko-se-se-kucan-prime-za-glavo/|title=Gledali\u0161\u010de Murgle 2. del: Uva\u017ea se veliko migrantov, izva\u017ea veliko izobra\u017eenih \u2013 ko se \u0161e Ku\u010dan prime za glavo|date=2018-05-29|work=Nova24TV|access-date=2018-06-04|language=sl-SI}}</ref>\n\n=== Other radical beliefs ===\nSDS MP Branko Grims, speaking to a gathering of a patriotic ultranationalist group in early 2018, said \"Now is the era of Trump. He is the greatest thorn in the foot of the [[globalists]], who control the US mechanisms, with Soros at the helm. Soros is the symbol of this. But there's also the Rothschilds and many other wealthiest families of financial speculators.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vecer.com/domoljubje-midva-se-ljubiva-6406751|title=Domoljubje: midva se ljubiva|last=|first=|date=2018-02-17|work=Ve\u010der|access-date=2018-06-04|language=sl-si}}</ref> SDS MP Marijan Pojbi\u010d, in a 2017 Statehood Day address on Facebook, called for \"No more mayors that aren't real Slovenes, and even fewer national politicians who aren't real Slovenes by birth.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vecer.com/tudi-to-je-mozno-poslanec-cerajeve-stranke-se-je-opravicil-za-zaljivi-tvit-6277480|title=Tudi to je mo\u017eno: Poslanec Cerarjeve stranke se je opravi\u010dil za \u017ealjivi tvit|last=|first=|date=2017-07-05|work=Ve\u010der|access-date=2018-06-04|language=sl-si}}</ref>\n\nAfter the 2011 parliamentary elections, which saw the victory of Ljubljana mayor Zoran Jankovi\u0107 (who is of Serbian descent) and his party,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://english.sta.si/1683795/ljubljana-mayor-entering-race-for-parliament|title=STA: Ljubljana Mayor Entering Race for Parliament|date=2011-10-11|website=english.sta.si|language=en|access-date=2018-06-07}}</ref><ref name=\":11\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.mladina.si/107690/moteci-trenirkarji/|title=Mote\u010di trenirkarji|last=|first=|date=2011-12-16|work=Mladina.si|access-date=2018-06-06|language=sl}}</ref> a contribution published on the official SDS webpage by a \"Toma\u017e Majer\" caused considerable public outrage.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dnevnik.si/1042494725|title=Informacijska poobla\u0161\u010denka \u017ee ovadila pisca spornega \u010dlanka|last=|first=|date=2011-12-12|work=Dnevnik|access-date=2018-06-06|language=sl}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sta.si/1705201/v-clanku-na-spletni-strani-sds-po-turkovem-mnenju-elementi-sovraznega-govora|title=V \u010dlanku na spletni strani SDS po T\u00fcrkovem mnenju elementi sovra\u017enega govora|date=2011-12-12|website=www.sta.si|language=sl|access-date=2018-06-06}}</ref><ref name=\":37\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.dnevnik.si/1042494937/slovenija/1042494937|title=Gibanje trenirk s spleta do vrha dr\u017eave|last=Andren\u0161ek|first=Anita|date=2011-12-13|work=Dnevnik|access-date=2018-06-07|language=sl}}</ref><ref name=\":38\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.dnevnik.si/1042496335|title=Trenirke Toma\u017ea Majerja|last=|first=|date=2011-12-19|work=Dnevnik|access-date=2018-06-07|language=sl}}</ref> Majer states that Jankovi\u0107 was elected by \"well-disciplined new citizens\" living in \"high-rise neighbourhoods\", tracksuit-clad voters (in Slovenia, a common stereotype of immigr\u00e9s from Southern republics{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}}) with foreign accents arriving at polling places in groups holding notes with instructions on whom to vote for. These \"new citizens\" were allegedly mobilised by being admonished their citizenship will be revoked if \"the right\" is elected.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dnevnik.si/1042494618/slovenija/1042494618|title=Analiza nestrpnosti na spletni strani SDS|last=Petkovi\u010d|first=Bla\u017e|date=2011-12-12|work=Dnevnik|access-date=2018-06-06|language=sl}}</ref><ref name=\":11\" /> Majer further states that one of his acquaintances (who is of Bosnian descent) was even offered monetary reward to vote for Jankovi\u0107. Majer also claims that the roughly 1/3 of Jankovi\u0107 voters of Slovenian descent were ordered to vote for PS by Milan Ku\u010dan and Janez Stanovnik.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sds.si/news/10328|title=Jankovi\u0107a sta dvignila umetno ustvarjen strah in slovenska radodarnost z dr\u017eavljanstvi|last=Majer|first=Toma\u017e|date=2011-12-09|work=www.sds.si|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111211105751/http://www.sds.si/news/10328|archive-date=2011-12-11}}</ref> Several media organisations attempted to identify the author, but were unsuccessful.<ref name=\":11\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://old.slovenskenovice.si/novice/slovenija/kunstelj-pravi-da-je-tomaz-majer-jansa|title=Kunstelj pravi, da je Toma\u017e Majer Jan\u0161a|last=|first=|date=2011-12-13|work=Slovenske novice|access-date=2018-06-06|language=sl}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dnevnik.si/1042494881|title=Kdo je Toma\u017e Majer?|last=|first=|date=2011-12-13|work=Dnevnik|access-date=2018-06-06|language=sl}}</ref> It has been speculated that the real author of the text was in fact Janez Jan\u0161a, based on similar known past statements (specifically, his 1993 commentary on the poor electoral performance of SDS during the 1992 elections).<ref name=\":11\" /> In the wake of the 2011 election, Jan\u0161a and several other SDS MPs and candidates expressed similar but somewhat toned-down nationalistic sentiments while commenting on the election and its winner.<ref name=\":11\" /> The public reaction culminated in a \"March of the Tracksuits\", a rally where participants attended clothed in tracksuits to protest against division and intolerance.<ref name=\":37\" /><ref name=\":38\" />\n\n== Organization and political affiliation ==\nAs of 2013, SDS membership numbered some 30,000 strong, more than any other political party in Slovenia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://reporter.si/clanek/slovenija/sds-z-vec-kot-30000-clani-dl-jih-ima-komaj-921-446352|title=SDS z ve\u010d kot 30.000 \u010dlani, DL jih ima komaj 921|website=Revija Reporter|language=sl-SI|access-date=2018-06-05}}</ref> [[Slovenian Democratic Youth]] ({{lang-sl|Slovenska demokratska mladina}}, SDM) is the independent and autonomous [[youth wing]] of the party.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sdm.si/program/|title=Program|work=Slovenska demokratska mladina|access-date=2018-06-03|language=sl-si}}</ref>\n\nThe party is affiliated with the [[Jo\u017ee Pu\u010dnik Institute]], the major [[liberal conservatism|liberal-conservative]] think tank in Slovenia.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.martenscentre.eu/members/jo%C5%BEe-pucnik-institute|title=Jo\u017ee Pucnik Institute {{!}} Martens Centre|work=Martens Centre|access-date=2018-06-04|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://institutpucnik.si/|title=In\u0161titut dr. Jo\u017eeta Pu\u010dnika|website=institutpucnik.si|language=sl-SI|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mladina.si/90846/institut-dr-jozeta-pucnika/|title=In\u0161titut dr. Jo\u017eeta Pu\u010dnika|work=Mladina.si|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dnevnik.si/1042598110|title=Davkopla\u010devalci izdatno financirali zasebni in\u0161titut SDS|work=Dnevnik|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mladina.si/95396/joze-pucnik-kot-by-pass/|title=Jo\u017ee Pu\u010dnik kot by-pass|work=Mladina.si|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref> It is also closely affiliated with the civic platform [[Rally for the Republic (Slovenia)|Rally for the Republic]] ({{lang|sl|Zbor za republiko}}).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dnevnik.si/1042575432|title=V SDS potrdili, da bo udele\u017eence Zbora za republiko nagovoril tudi Jan\u0161a, \u010deprav naj bi bil takrat v Bruslju|work=Dnevnik|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.rtvslo.si/slovenija/zbor-za-republiko-volivce-nagovarja-k-podpori-sds-a-nsi-ja-in-sls-a/454965|title=Zbor za republiko volivce nagovarja k podpori SDS-a, NSi-ja in SLS-a|work=Prvi interaktivni multimedijski portal, MMC RTV Slovenija|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.24ur.com/sds-nismo-organizatorji-zborovanja-se-ga-bomo-pa-z-veseljem-udelezili.html|title=SDS pripravlja zborovanje pod krinko Zbora za republiko|website=www.24ur.com|language=sl|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref> Committee 2014 (Slovene: ''Odbor 2014'') is a civic organisation that was established to protest and demand the overturn of the corruption convictions in the [[Patria case]], the freeing of SDS leader Janez Jan\u0161a from prison (sentence resuling from the conviction), and the \"actual implementation of the rule of law, human rights, basic freedoms, and establishment of a democratic society\".<ref name=\"auto5\">{{Cite web|url=http://odbor2014.si/sub/296/o-nas|title=O nas|website=odbor2014.si|language=en|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref><ref name=\":22\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.mladina.si/160375/politika-pred-sodiscem/|title=Politika pred sodi\u0161\u010dem|work=Mladina.si|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref> Committee 2014 held regular protests in front of the Higher Court building in Ljubljana.<ref name=\"auto5\"/><ref name=\":22\" /> The Alliance for the Values of Slovene Independence (Slovene: ''Zdru\u017eenje za vrednote Slovenske osamosvojitve'', VSO) is a patriotic veteran non-governmental organisation intended to commemorate the values of the Slovenian independence movement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vso.si/index.php/vso/statut|title=Statut|last=User|first=Super|website=www.vso.si|language=sl-SI|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref><ref name=\"auto6\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.mladina.si/152646/cigave-vrednote/|title=\u010cigave vrednote?|work=Mladina.si|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref> VSO leadership consists of prominent SDS members and associates. The organisation holds public speaking events, commemorations, and is engaged in other activities as well.<ref name=\"auto6\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://siol.net/novice/slovenija/zdruzenje-vso-obelezilo-obletnico-prvega-postroja-slovenske-vojske-431939|title=Zdru\u017eenje VSO obele\u017eilo obletnico prvega postroja Slovenske vojske|access-date=2018-06-04|language=sl}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.delo.si/novice/politika/zdruzenje-vso-kazensko-ovadilo-milana-kucana.html|title=Zdru\u017eenje VSO kazensko ovadilo Milana Ku\u010dana|last=\u010c.|first=Ma. F., STA, N.|access-date=2018-06-04|language=sl-si}}</ref>\n\nSDS has seen some support from the Slovene Catholic Church.<ref name=\":25\" /><ref name=\":46\" /> The party is supported by and closely affiliated with Hungarian Prime Minister [[Viktor Orb\u00e1n]] ([[Fidesz]]).<ref name=\":35\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/slovenian-survivor-targets-victory-a-la-orban/|title=Slovenian survivor targets victory \u00e0 la Orb\u00e1n|date=1 June 2018|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=\":7\"/><ref name=\":9\" /><ref name=\":12\" /><ref name=\":10\" /><ref name=\"auto7\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2018/06/01/world/europe/ap-eu-slovenia-election.html|title=Anti-Immigrant Party Set to Make Gains in Slovenia Vote|date=2018-06-01|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-06-03|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\"auto8\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.rtvslo.si/news-in-english/jansa-re-elected-as-president-of-sds/422902|title=Jan\u0161a re-elected as president of SDS :: Prvi interaktivni multimedijski portal, MMC RTV Slovenija|website=www.rtvslo.si|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref> SDS's committed backing of Fidesz has reportedly been the decisive factor in preventing Fidesz's expulsion from the [[European People's Party]], resulting in a more lenient suspension.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mladina.si/190431/hungary-s-attempt-to-control-slovenian-media/|title=Hungary's attempt to control Slovenian media|website=Mladina.si|access-date=2019-04-07}}</ref> In a letter to the EPP leader, Jan\u0161a warned of an \"inevitable\" split in the EPP if the vote to expel Fidesz were to take place.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.euractiv.com/section/politics/news/exclusive-slovenian-center-right-cancel-orban-vote-or-epp-is-inevitably-split/|title=EXCLUSIVE-Slovenian centre-right: Cancel Orb\u00e1n vote or EPP is 'inevitably' split|last=Trkanjec|first=Zeljko|date=2019-03-20|website=euractiv.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-04-07}}</ref>\n\n=== Affiliated publications ===\nSDS is also affiliated with several current and past publications, including its de facto party publication, [[Demokracija]],<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=https://siol.net/posel-danes/novice/strankarsko-glasilo-sds-v-roke-madzarskega-tabloida-445381|title=Strankarsko glasilo SDS v roke mad\u017earskega tabloida|access-date=2018-06-02|language=sl}}</ref> and tabloid \u0160kandal24<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vecer.com/demokracija-nova24tv-in-skandal24-jansevi-stali-in-obstali-z-orbanom-6305092|title=Demokracija, Nova24TV in \u0160kandal24: Jan\u0161evi \"stali in obstali\" z Orbanom|work=\u010casnik Ve\u010der d.o.o.|access-date=2018-06-02|language=sl-si}}</ref> (both owned by ''Nova Obzorja'' (English: \"New Horizonts\") publishing company, which is in turn jointly owned by SDS and a Hungarian publishing company with close ties to Hungary's ruling party, [[Fidesz]]).<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":35\" /> The publishing company has profited from providing literature to, and advising the SDS parliamentary group/SDS MPs (activities for which parliamentary groups receive state funds), and has also benefited financially from doing business with government agencies, which were particularly bountiful while SDS was in government.<ref name=\"Dnevnik\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.dnevnik.si/1042597256|title=Dobi\u010dkonosne prilo\u017enosti hi\u0161ne zalo\u017ebe SDS|work=Dnevnik|access-date=2018-09-05}}</ref> [[Nova24TV]], a media conglomerate consisting of a television channel and online news portal, was established by SDS MPs and members, and party sympathisers, and later also received financial injections from Hungarian Fidesz-affiliated companies.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://siol.net/posel-danes/novice/orbanovi-mediji-v-lastnistvo-nova24tv-438752|title=Orbanovi mediji v lastni\u0161tvo Nova24TV|access-date=2018-06-02|language=sl}}</ref><ref name=\":35\" /> Additionally, the SDS-friendly political web portal Politikis is also owned and managed by a close SDS associate.<ref name=\":21\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dnevnik.si/1042794266|title=SDS v predvolilno kampanjo z mno\u017eico lokalnih portalov|work=Dnevnik|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.delo.si/novice/politika/sds-v-drzavnem-zboru-zaposlila-dejana-kaloha-politikis.html|title=SDS v dr\u017eavnem zboru zaposlila Dejana Kaloha (Politikis)|last=politika|first=An\u017ee Bo\u017ei\u010d, notranja|access-date=2018-06-03|language=sl-si}}</ref> Slovenski tednik and Ekspres, free newspapers distributed in the run-up to the [[2008 Slovenian parliamentary election|2008 parliamentary election]], were also later found to have been directly linked to SDS and its electoral efforts.<ref name=\":21\" /><ref name=\"auto\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dnevnik.si/1042475665|title=Brezpla\u010dnika sta bila del predvolilne kampanje SDS|work=Dnevnik|access-date=2018-06-02}}</ref> As with Slovenski tednik and Ekspres, \u0160kandal24 announced it will cease print publication the day after the 2018 parliamentary election, only continuing as an online publication.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mladina.si/185826/v-slogu-zloglasnih-brezplacnikov-po-volitvah-ugasnil-tudi-skandal24/|title=V slogu zloglasnih brezpla\u010dnikov po volitvah ugasnil tudi \u0160kandal24|work=Mladina.si|access-date=2018-06-05}}</ref> In late 2017, an array of over a dozen local/regional web news portals with a common template was also set up, with editors of all linked to SDS based on publicly available information.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dnevnik.si/1042794266|title=SDS v predvolilno kampanjo z mno\u017eico lokalnih portalov|website=Dnevnik|access-date=2019-01-21}}</ref><ref name=\":45\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mladina.si/184953/orb-nov-jansa/|title=Orb\u00e1nov Jan\u0161a|website=Mladina.si|access-date=2019-01-21}}</ref> The websites mostly contained informative content, publishing local news with occasional articles that promoted SDS' candidates and narrative/agenda subtly mixed in.<ref name=\":45\" /> The sites may have been set up primarily as a political propaganda effort in anticipation of the [[2018 Slovenian local elections]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.delo.si/prosti-cas/zanimivosti/opazili-smo-sds-gre-na-lokalne-volitve.html|title=Opazili smo: SDS gre na lokalne volitve|last=Delo.si|date=2017-12-11|website=www.delo.si|language=sl-si|access-date=2019-01-21}}</ref>\n\n== Supporters and affiliates ==\nThe party enjoys strong support in some Slovene [[Conservatism|conservative]] and [[Classical liberalism|classical liberal]] intellectual circles. Public figures who have publicly voiced support for SDS or affiliated themselves with the party include economist [[Ljubo Sirc]] (joined the party in 2010),<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.zurnal24.si/slovenija/umrl-svetovno-znani-ekonomist-in-disident-dr-ljubo-sirc-281977|title=Umrl svetovno znani ekonomist in disident dr. Ljubo Sirc|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=2018-06-03|language=sl}}</ref> philosopher [[Ivan Urban\u010di\u010d]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sds.si/novica/zapustil-nas-je-prof-dr-ivan-urbancic-12377|title=Zapustil nas je prof. dr. Ivan Urban\u010di\u010d {{!}} SDS|website=www.sds.si|language=sl|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://siol.net/trendi/kultura/umrl-filozof-in-prevajalec-ivan-urbancic-423357|title=Umrl filozof in prevajalec Ivan Urban\u010di\u010d|access-date=2018-06-03|language=sl}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nova24tv.si/slovenija/ljudje/umrl-je-slovenski-filozof-in-pucnikov-osebni-prijatelj-ivan-urbancic/|title=Umrl je filozof in Pu\u010dnikov osebni prijatelj Ivan Urban\u010di\u010d {{!}} Nova24TV|date=2016-08-08|work=Nova24TV|access-date=2018-06-03|language=sl-SI}}</ref> historians [[Vasko Simoniti]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sds.si/dogodek/dr-vasko-simoniti-na-arsovem-forumu-v-zivo-15565|title=Dr. Vasko Simoniti na Arsovem forumu v \u017eivo {{!}} SDS|website=www.sds.si|language=sl|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://demokracija.si/nova/index.php/fokus/vasko-simoniti-zdenko-roter-se-hoce-prikazati-kot-dober-udbovec|title=Vasko Simoniti: Zdenko Roter se ho\u010de prikazati kot dober udbovec|last=J.B.|access-date=2018-06-03|language=sl-si}}</ref> and [[Alenka Puhar]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.politikis.si/2013/06/alenka-puhar-ni-pravih-dokazov-za-obsodbo-janse-sodisca-delajo-kar-hocejo/|title=Alenka Puhar: Ni pravih dokazov za obsodbo Jan\u0161e! Sodi\u0161\u010da delajo kar ho\u010dejo. {{!}} Politikis|website=www.politikis.si|language=sl-SI|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sds.si/index.php/novica/alenka-puhar-imenovanje-stvari-z-njihovimi-imeni-12411|title=Alenka Puhar: Imenovanje stvari z njihovimi imeni {{!}} SDS|website=www.sds.si|language=sl|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sds.si/galerija/pucnikov-simpozij-2017-13571|title=Pu\u010dnikov simpozij 2017 {{!}} SDS|website=www.sds.si|language=sl|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref> writer and essayist [[Drago Jan\u010dar]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vecer.com/med-literarnim-kanonom-in-blagovno-znamko-6444457|title=Drago Jan\u010dar: Med literarnim kanonom in blagovno znamko|work=\u010casnik Ve\u010der d.o.o.|access-date=2018-06-03|language=sl-si}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dnevnik.si/1042598110|title=Davkopla\u010devalci izdatno financirali zasebni in\u0161titut SDS|work=Dnevnik|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref> theologian and philosopher [[Janez Juhant]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sds.si/novica/dr-janez-juhant-podpiram-delo-janeza-janse-2044|title=Dr. Janez Juhant: \"Podpiram delo Janeza Jan\u0161e\" {{!}} SDS|website=www.sds.si|language=sl|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.politikis.si/2014/10/dr-janez-juhant-slovenija-v-letu-2014-je-kot-orwellova-komunisticna-oceanija-vse-je-pod-nadzorom/|title=Dr. Janez Juhant: Slovenija v letu 2014 je kot Orwellova komunisti\u010dna Oceanija \u2013 vse je pod nadzorom! {{!}} Politikis|website=www.politikis.si|language=sl-SI|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref> and poet [[Tone Kuntner]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.delo.si/kultura/knjizevni-listi/tone-kuntner-ce-je-pomlad-samo-jj-je-kot-narod-nismo-vredni.html|title=Tone Kuntner: \u010ce je Pomlad samo JJ, je kot narod nismo vredni|last=kultura|first=Peter Kol\u0161ek|access-date=2018-06-03|language=sl-si}}</ref> Public supporters of the party also include sportsmen [[Miran Pavlin]],<ref name=\":18\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.zurnal24.si/slovenija/jansev-nogometni-up-83465|title=Jan\u0161ev nogometni up|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=2018-06-03|language=sl}}</ref><ref name=\":19\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.vecer.com/z-zlatkom-sva-bolj-umirjena-6260418|title=Miran Pavlin v intervjuju: Z Zlatkom sva bolj umirjena|work=\u010casnik Ve\u010der d.o.o.|access-date=2018-06-03|language=sl-si}}</ref> and [[Katja Koren]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mladina.si/54009/zvezdniki-v-politiki/|title=\"Zvezdniki\" v politiki|work=Mladina.si|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rtvslo.si/evropske-volitve/katja-koren-miklavec-sds/99981|title=Katja Koren Miklavec (SDS)|work=Prvi interaktivni multimedijski portal, MMC RTV Slovenija|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref> pop singer [[Marta Zore]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.delo.si/kultura/glasba/politiki-in-glasba-za-stranko-ali-za-denar.html|title=Politiki in glasba: Za stranko ali za denar?|last=Kenda|first=Vid|access-date=2018-06-03|language=sl-si}}</ref> designer and cartoonist [[Miki Muster]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sds.si/novica/poslovil-se-je-pionir-slovenskega-stripa-miki-muster-15718|title=Poslovil se je pionir slovenskega stripa Miki Muster {{!}} SDS|website=www.sds.si|language=sl|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref> and actor [[Roman Kon\u010dar]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mladina.si/111288/boj-za-nacin-razmisljanja/|title=Boj za na\u010din razmi\u0161ljanja|work=Mladina.si|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, SDS was found to have falsely attributed \"supporter status\" to many prominent Slovenes on its webpage. The party sent a request to comment on the ruling government for its party newspaper to numerous notable public figures. Though they were never asked whether they support the party or informed they will be listed as supporters, SDS nevertheless listed them as such.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dnevnik.si/1042203675|title=Ocenjevali vlado in postali podporniki SDS|work=Dnevnik|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref>\n\n=== Former supporters and affiliates ===\nMany prominent members have abandoned SDS due to the radicalisation of the party's ideology and disagreements over leadership style. Some also established new political parties. Most former members politically transitioned towards the centre, with a minority outflanking SDS on the far right.<ref name=\":57\">{{Cite web|url=https://china-cee.eu/2019/05/03/slovenia-political-briefing-changes-at-the-far-right-of-the-political-spectrum/|title=Slovenia political briefing: Changes at the far right of the political spectrum \u2013 China-CEE Institute|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref>\n\nFormer supporters or affiliated individuals, now party critics and dissidents, include one of the fathers of the current Slovenian Constitution, [[Peter Jambrek]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mladina.si/162993/dr-peter-jambrek/|title=Dr. Peter Jambrek|work=Mladina.si|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dnevnik.si/1042797967|title=Peter Jambrek o tem, da je SDS glede na socialni status bolj leva stranka|work=Dnevnik|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://siol.net/novice/volitve-2018/koga-bosta-volila-milan-kucan-in-peter-jambrek-468504|title=Koga bosta volila Milan Ku\u010dan in Peter Jambrek|access-date=2018-06-03|language=sl}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://novice.svet24.si/clanek/novice/slovenija/5616aa6ebff37/sds-v-slepi-ulici|title=Z Jan\u0161o je konec|work=Svet24.si|access-date=2018-06-03|language=sl-SI}}</ref> the former chairman of [[Rally for the Republic (Slovenia)|Rally for the Republic]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dnevnik.si/1042488253|title=Zbor za republiko ne bo podprl stranke Gregorja Viranta|work=Dnevnik|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref> and [[Civic List (Slovenia)|Civic List]] party leader<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rtvslo.si/slovenija/foto-stranka-ustanovljena-virant-predsednik-sustersic-podpredsednik/268939|title=Foto: Stranka ustanovljena, Virant predsednik, \u0160u\u0161ter\u0161i\u010d podpredsednik|work=Prvi interaktivni multimedijski portal, MMC RTV Slovenija|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref> [[Gregor Virant]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mladina.si/106358/gregor-virant-distanciral-sem-se-od-sds/|title=Gregor Virant: \"Distanciral sem se od SDS\"|work=Mladina.si|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref><ref name=\":57\" /> and liberal economist [[Jo\u017ee P. Damijan]].<ref name=\"Guardiancich2012\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mladina.si/43635/metamorfoze-jozeta-p-damijana/|title=Metamorfoze Jo\u017eeta P. Damijana|work=Mladina.si|access-date=2018-06-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mladina.si/95355/dokoncno-slovo-mladoekonomistov/|title=Dokon\u010dno slovo mladoekonomistov|work=Mladina.si|access-date=2018-06-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.delo.si/novice/slovenija/damijan-nepreklicno-odstopil.html|title=Damijan nepreklicno odstopil|last=Uredni\u0161tvo|access-date=2018-06-02|language=sl-si}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rtvslo.si/slovenija/joze-p-damijan-vendarle-odstopil/51782|title=Jo\u017ee P. Damijan vendarle odstopil|work=Prvi interaktivni multimedijski portal, MMC RTV Slovenija|access-date=2018-06-02}}</ref> [[Miha Brejc]] became ''persona non grata'' after his son-in-law [[Gregor Virant]] distanced himself from Jan\u0161a and established the [[Civic List (Slovenia)|Civic List]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mladina.si/112267/miha-brejc-izstopil-iz-sds/|title=Miha Brejc izstopil iz SDS|work=Mladina.si|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref> Other prominent former members include former Minister of Foreign Affairs [[Dimitrij Rupel]],<ref name=\":57\" /> former Minister of Internal Affairs [[Dragutin Mate]] (now a critic),<ref name=\"mate\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.24ur.com/novice/slovenija/dragutin-mate-izstopil-iz-sds.html|title=Dragutin Mate izstopil iz SDS: 'Notranja demokracija je za\u010dela pe\u0161ati'|website=www.24ur.com|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref> and Minister of Education [[\u017diga Turk]],<ref name=\":57\" /> former MEP [[Romana Jordan Cizelj]],<ref name=\":57\" /> former SDS MPs [[Andrej \u010cu\u0161]] (now a critic),<ref name=\":57\" /> and [[Ivo Hvalica]] (now a critic),<ref name=\"dnevnik.si\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dnevnik.si/1042790577|title=Ivo Hvalica: Jan\u0161o so opevali kot Mao Cetunga|website=Dnevnik|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref><ref name=\":57\" /> and Pu\u010dnik's  \"mother of the party\" Vera Ban.<ref name=\":58\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.24ur.com/novice/slovenija/vera-ban-kriticno-o-sds-in-janezu-jansi.html|title=VIDEO: Vera Ban kriti\u010dno o Jan\u0161i: Saj vendarle samo en \u010dlovek ne more vsega vedeti, vsega znati, vsega \u010dutiti|website=www.24ur.com|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref> Former public supporters also include sportsman [[Miran Pavlin]].<ref name=\":18\" /><ref name=\":19\" />\n\n== Controversies and criticism ==\n=== Ties to extremist groups ===\nSDS has been criticised for alleged links to a neo-Nazi extremist group; [[Far-right politics in Slovenia#Blood & Honour|the Slovene branch of Blood & Honour]].<ref name=\":12\"/><ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/greenslade/2014/sep/15/press-freedom-slovenia|title=Slovenian journalist facing jail for revealing party's neo-Nazi links|last=Greenslade|first=Roy|date=2014-09-15|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-06-02}}</ref> The journalist who uncovered the links (Anu\u0161ka Deli\u0107) was charged with leaking confidential information.<ref name=\":13\" /><ref name=\":12\"/> The state intelligence agency, [[Slovenian Intelligence and Security Agency|SOVA]], headed by an SDS appointee at the time of the indictment,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mladina.si/160578/neonacisti-na-varnem/|title=Neonacisti na varnem|work=Mladina.si|access-date=2018-06-02}}</ref> inadvertently confirmed allegations made by Deli\u0107 by stating that the information revealed in the reports was consistent with findings of an ongoing investigation into the activities of the violent extremist group.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.delo.si/novice/politika/ugotovitve-do-katerih-je-prislo-delo-sova-potrjuje.html|title=Neonacisti pri nas: Sova potrjuje ugotovitve Dela|last=politika|first=Mario Belovi\u010d, Rok Kajzer, notranja|access-date=2018-06-02|language=sl-si}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.delo.si/novice/slovenija/zaradi-razkrivanja-neonacisticne-mreze-preganjajo-novinarko-dela.html|title=Zaradi razkrivanja neonacisti\u010dne mre\u017ee preganjajo novinarko Dela|last=kronika|first=Klara \u0160krinjar, notranja politika, Iva Ropac|access-date=2018-06-02|language=sl-si}}</ref> SOVA argued that the information revealed in the reports could not have been obtained by any other means than by gaining access to information collected during the agency's covert investigations, and that the publication disrupted its efforts to monitor the group by alerting B & H of the monitoring efforts.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dnevnik.si/1042688464|title=Predobravnavni narok zoper Deli\u0107evo: predlagali zasli\u0161anje T\u00fcrka, Pahorja in Masle\u0161e|work=Dnevnik|access-date=2018-06-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://siol.net/novice/crna-kronika/nekdanja-direktorja-sove-razkrivanje-tajnih-podatkov-lahko-ogrozi-zivljenja-67863|title=Nekdanja direktorja Sove: Razkrivanje tajnih podatkov lahko ogrozi \u017eivljenja|access-date=2018-06-02|language=sl}}</ref> Deli\u0107 alleged the charges were \"politically motivated\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rtvslo.si/crna-kronika/anuska-delic-ovadba-je-politicno-motivirana/355056|title=Anu\u0161ka Deli\u0107: Ovadba je politi\u010dno motivirana|work=Prvi interaktivni multimedijski portal, MMC RTV Slovenija|access-date=2018-06-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dnevnik.si/1042702263|title=Anu\u0161ka Deli\u0107: ovadba je politi\u010dno motivirana, to\u017eilstvo bi moralo postopek ustaviti|work=Dnevnik|access-date=2018-06-02}}</ref>\n\nSome Blood & Honour members were allegedly also members of SDS,<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.dnevnik.si/1042492052|title=Nasprotujo\u010de si informacije: So v SDS-ov podmladek v\u010dlanjeni tudi neonacisti?|work=Dnevnik|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.delo.si/ozadja/v-blizini-neonacistov-in-vrha-politike.html|title=V bli\u017eini neonacistov in vrha politike|last=Ozadja|first=Anu\u0161ka Deli\u0107, Rok Kajzer|access-date=2018-06-03|language=sl-si}}</ref> and formally met with SDS MP Branko Grims.<ref name=\":14\" /><ref name=\"auto9\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.delo.si/novice/politika/ugotovitve-do-katerih-je-prislo-delo-sova-potrjuje.html|title=Neonacisti pri nas: Sova potrjuje ugotovitve Dela|last=politika|first=Mario Belovi\u010d, Rok Kajzer, notranja|access-date=2018-06-03|language=sl-si}}</ref> The group (the members of which allegedly received training by members of the Slovenian armed forces on an army [[Proving ground|training area]], borrowed army weaponry (a rocket launcher), attempted to purchase handguns, and were in direct correspondence with [[Anders Behring Breivik|Anders Breivik]] by both mail and e-mail, with multiple B & H members receiving his manifesto before Breivik's killing spree<ref name=\"auto9\"/><ref name=\"auto10\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.mladina.si/160578/neonacisti-na-varnem/|title=Neonacisti na varnem|work=Mladina.si|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref>) was allegedly intimately implicated in orchestrating the violent riots which took place amid the [[2012\u201313 Slovenian protests]].<ref name=\"auto9\"/><ref name=\"auto10\"/> The organised group of violent agitators that disrupted a major protest in Ljubljana was also suspected of having been trained, hired, and compensated, possibly by a political party, according to unofficial sources within the police.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mladina.si/118519/neonacisti-so-tu/|title=Neonacisti so tu|work=Mladina.si|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref>\n\nMore recently, SDS has also fostered ties with [[Far-right politics in Slovenia#Generation Identity Slovenia|Generation Identity Slovenia]], the Slovenian chapter of the far-right [[Identitarian movement]] organisations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://siol.net/novice/slovenija/generacija-identitete-skrajno-gibanje-ki-je-z-volitvami-v-sloveniji-dobilo-nov-zagon-467050|title=Generacija identitete: skrajno gibanje, ki je z volitvami v Sloveniji dobilo nov zagon|access-date=2018-06-03|language=sl}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vecer.com/za-europol-desnicarski-ekstremisti-s-stranko-sds-pa-soorganizatorji-dogodkov-6642112|title=Za Europol desni\u010darski ekstremisti, s stranko SDS pa soorganizatorji dogodkov|date=2019-01-10|website=www.vecer.com|language=sl-si|access-date=2019-01-20}}</ref> In August 2018, the party's publishing company, New Horizons,<ref name=\"Dnevnik\"/> anonymously published the Slovene Identitarians' alt-right book, ''Manifesto for the Homeland''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nova24tv.si/slovenija/jutri-izide-knjiga-za-katero-levicarji-grozijo-da-bi-jo-morali-prepovedali-prihaja-manifest-za-domovino/|title=[Video] Danes izide knjiga, za katero levi\u010darji grozijo, da bi jo morali prepovedati; Prihaja Manifest za domovino! {{!}} Nova24TV|date=2018-08-28|work=Nova24TV|access-date=2018-09-05|language=sl-SI}}</ref><ref name=\":999\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.mladina.si/187087/manifest-za-slovenijo-alpe-pa-francoske/|title=Manifest za Slovenijo, Alpe pa francoske|work=Mladina.si|access-date=2018-09-05}}</ref> The book was also promoted by SDS-affiliated media organisations and individuals, including SDS leader Janez Jan\u0161a,<ref name=\":999\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mladina.si/187229/manifest-nove-desnice/|title=Manifest nove desnice|work=Mladina.si|access-date=2018-09-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vecer.com/nova-obzorja-na-trg-s-knjigo-skupine-ki-siri-sovrazni-govor-6553758|title=Nova obzorja na trg s knjigo skupine, ki \u0161iri sovra\u017eni govor|work=\u010casnik Ve\u010der d.o.o.|access-date=2018-09-09|language=sl-si}}</ref> with SDS MP \u017dan Mahni\u010d even going so far as to post on Twitter a photo of the book taken from his parliamentary seat, with the floor of the parliamentary chamber in the background.<ref name=\"Mladina.si\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.mladina.si/187348/kaj-je-identitetno-gibanje-ki-je-navdusilo-zana-mahnica/|title=Kaj je identitetno gibanje, ki je navdu\u0161ilo \u017dana Mahni\u010da|work=Mladina.si|access-date=2018-09-14}}</ref> The leader of the Austrian Identitarians, Martin Sellner, publicly thanked Jan\u0161a for his support on Twitter. Sellner was at the time being investigated by Austrian authorities and ostracised by the ruling conservative [[Freedom Party of Austria]] for his financial ties with the [[Christchurch mosque shootings|Christchurch terrorist]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://siol.net/novice/slovenija/vodja-avstrijskih-identitarcev-hvala-gospod-janez-jansa-ste-casten-clovek-494404|title=Vodja identitarcev v Avstriji: Hvala, gospod Janez Jan\u0161a. Ste \u010dasten \u010dlovek. #video|website=siol.net|language=sl|access-date=2019-04-07}}</ref>\n\n=== Political self-dealing accusations ===\nThe party has been accused of political self-dealing and nepotism, appointing relatives, allies, and friends to government (and other) positions. Many close relatives of prominent SDS members have found employment in the Slovenian and European parliaments, high ranking public sector positions, and state-owned companies (some despite not meeting the official job requirements).<ref name=\":20\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mladina.si/182937/nepotisticna-hobotnica/|title=Nepotisti\u010dna hobotnica|work=Mladina.si|access-date=2018-06-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mladina.si/120739/nepotizem/|title=Nepotizem|work=Mladina.si|access-date=2018-06-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vecer.com/poleg-zana-janse-delata-za-tomcevo-tudi-petkov-sin-in-brat-jerajeve-6352314|title=Poleg \u017dana Jan\u0161e delata za Tom\u010devo tudi Petkov sin in brat Jerajeve|work=\u010casnik Ve\u010der d.o.o.|access-date=2018-06-05|language=sl-si}}</ref><ref name=\":36\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.mladina.si/49135/prvo-leto-kadrovanja/|title=Prvo leto kadrovanja|work=Mladina.si|access-date=2018-06-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.finance.si/216166|title=Eles, kadrovska trdnjava SDS in NSi?|website=Finance.si|language=sl-SI|access-date=2019-01-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mladina.si/91033/clanstvo-v-sds-pogoj-za-sefa/|title=\u010clanstvo v SDS pogoj za \u0161efa|website=Mladina.si|access-date=2019-01-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mladina.si/94637/zeleznicarski-puc/|title=\u017delezni\u010darski pu\u010d|website=Mladina.si|access-date=2019-01-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mladina.si/44134/kdo-kadruje-politicno/|title=Kdo kadruje politi\u010dno?|website=Mladina.si|access-date=2019-01-21}}</ref><ref name=\"Guardiancich2012\" />\n\nSDS has been accused of political firings and replacements in, and selective financing of many institutions under the public sphere, and creating an environment where politisation of the public workplace was permissible and pervasive while in power.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mladina.si/185777/kaj-pomeni-jansa-na-oblasti/|title=Kaj pomeni Jan\u0161a na oblasti?|work=Mladina.si|access-date=2018-06-06}}</ref><ref name=\":36\" />\n\n=== Cult of personality ===\nSDS leader Janez Jan\u0161a has continuously served as party head since 1993 without a single other contender for the post.<ref name=\"auto8\"/> Party members are extremely loyal to Jan\u0161a;<ref name=\":25\" /> it has been noted that the party appears to resemble a cult,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://english.sta.si/2389847/delo-sees-sds-trapped-by-jansa-cult-and-past|title=STA: Delo sees SDS trapped by Jan\u0161a cult and past|website=english.sta.si|language=en|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref><ref name=\"dnevnik.si\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sloveniatimes.com/tough-driver-for-a-rocky-road|title=Tough Driver for a Rocky Road|website=www.sloveniatimes.com|language=sl|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref> with numerous past members claiming that Jan\u0161a leads the party in an authoritarian manner and that no dissent is tolerated.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://siol.net/novice/slovenija/poslanec-andrej-cus-zapusca-sds-417954|title=Andrej \u010cu\u0161 zapu\u0161\u010da SDS in pravi: Nisem ne Jan\u0161eva ne Ku\u010danova lutka (video)|access-date=2018-06-05|language=sl}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.24ur.com/novice/slovenija/plaz-se-je-usul-andrej-cus-izstopil-iz-sds-vera-ban-ima-prav.html|title=\u010cu\u0161: Ni se mi zdelo prav, da grem v dr\u017eavni zbor in se po\u010dutim, kot da smo v letu 1990|website=www.24ur.com|language=sl|access-date=2018-06-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.domovina.je/besede-s-katerimi-so-sds-zapuscali-njeni-ugledni-clani/|title=Besede, s katerimi SDS zapu\u0161\u010dajo njeni ugledni \u010dlani {{!}} Domovina|last=Uredni\u0161tvo|website=www.domovina.je|language=sl-SI|access-date=2018-06-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://novice.svet24.si/clanek/novice/slovenija/57e3c715973f2/iz-sds-odhaja-tudi-znidar|title=Jan\u0161o spet zapu\u0161\u010dajo poslanci|work=Svet24.si|access-date=2018-06-05|language=sl-SI}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mladina.si/190325/nekdanji-poslanec-sds-jansa-ni-demokrat-temvec-avtokrat-ki-vse-odlocitve-sprejema-sam/|title=Nekdanji poslanec SDS: Jan\u0161a ni demokrat, temve\u010d avtokrat, ki vse odlo\u010ditve sprejema sam|website=Mladina.si|access-date=2019-04-01}}</ref><ref name=\":58\" /><ref name=\"mate\"/> SDS MEP [[Romana Jordan Cizelj]] was reportedly the only one within the party leadership to openly voice her doubts about Jan\u0161a's continued leadership of the party whilst serving a prison sentence for corruption. Jordan Cizelj was subsequently not allowed to run for reelection as MEP on the SDS ticket as punishment for her disloyalty to Jan\u0161a.<ref name=\":58\" />\n\n=== Campaign financing impropriety allegations ===\nIn the run-up to the 2018 Slovenian parliamentary election, SDS attempted to receive a loan of \u20ac450.000 from an individual residing in [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://english.sta.si/2469274/report-sds-obtains-loan-from-individual-in-bosnia|title=STA: Report: SDS obtains loan from individual in Bosnia|website=english.sta.si|language=en|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref> to fund its electoral campaign. The party came into contact with the individual via Nova obzorja publishing company (partially owned by SDS). SDS also put up its share in Nova obzorja as collateral.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.24ur.com/novice/slovenija/nenavadno-posojilo-stranke-sds-od-32-letnice-iz-bih-najeli-kar-450-000-evrov-kredita.html|title=32-letna Dijana \u0110u\u0111i\u0107, ki je Jan\u0161evi SDS posodila 450.000 evrov, je tudi znanka razvpitega Roka Sne\u017ei\u010da|website=www.24ur.com|language=sl|access-date=2018-06-05}}</ref> The sum borrowed exceeded limits set by campaign finance laws, however, and SDS was obliged to return the borrowed funds. A police and financial court investigation was also triggered after the terms of the loan became public.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://siol.net/novice/slovenija/sds-vrnil-sporno-posojilo-z-obrestmi-457338|title=SDS vrnila sporno posojilo z obrestmi #video|access-date=2018-06-03|language=sl}}</ref> An investigation into the lender was also launched, based on suspicions of money laundering, tax avoidance, destruction and falsification of business documents, and overseeing dummy companies.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://siol.net/posel-danes/novice/pranje-denarja-kaj-je-razkrila-parlamentarna-komisija-vzivo-467626|title=Pranje denarja: ve\u010d kazenskih ovadb gre na policijo #video|access-date=2018-06-03|language=sl}}</ref><ref name=\":15\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.24ur.com/novice/slovenija/dijana-dzudzic-naj-bi-z-razlicnih-racunov-dvignila-vec-kot-3-5-milijona-gotovine.html|title=Dijana \u0110u\u0111i\u010d naj bi z razli\u010dnih ra\u010dunov dvignila ve\u010d kot 3,5 milijona gotovine|website=www.24ur.com|language=sl|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref> The individual was allegedly a part of a criminal organisation managing dummy companies that received funds of undisclosed origins (including the funds later loaned to SDS).<ref name=\":15\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.delo.si/novice/slovenija/sds-si-je-denar-menda-izposodila-pri-muli-51788.html|title=SDS si je denar menda izposodila pri muli|last=Poti\u010d|first=Zoran|access-date=2018-06-03|language=sl-si}}</ref>\n\nLess than a week before the 2018 parliamentary election took place, it was revealed that media/publishing companies closely affiliated and partially owned by SDS received some \u20ac800.000 from two Hungarian nationals (or, rather, their companies) - both with close ties to Hungarian president [[Viktor Orb\u00e1n]] - months before the election, bringing the total amount SDS-affiliated media companies received from Hungarian entities to over \u20ac2.2M. The SDS-affiliated media companies that received the funds in turn purchased campaign adds for SDS. Nova obzorja publishing company also attempted to loan \u20ac60,000 to the party. The same Hungarian individuals also provided funds for political allies in Macedonia. It is furthermore also known that the loan SDS attempted to obtain from a Bosnian citizen some months earlier had a Hungarian connection.<ref name=\":35\" /><ref name=\":12\" /><ref name=\":34\">{{Cite web|url=https://english.sta.si/2519419/foreign-campaign-financing-forbidden-sds-denies-bypass|title=STA: Foreign campaign financing forbidden, SDS denies bypass|website=english.sta.si|language=en|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vecer.com/volitve-schatz-in-adamikova-vbrizgala-svez-denar-v-medijski-sistem-sds-6482056|title=Sve\u017e denar v medijskem sistemu SDS: Kdo je Agnes Adamik?|work=\u010casnik Ve\u010der d.o.o.|access-date=2018-06-03|language=sl-si}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mladina.si/185556/madzarski-dolznik/|title=Mad\u017earski dol\u017enik|work=Mladina.si|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://english.sta.si/2520180/alleged-hungarian-financing-of-sds-draws-ire-from-alde|title=STA: Alleged Hungarian financing of SDS draws ire from ALDE|website=english.sta.si|language=en|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref><ref name=\"auto7\"/><ref name=\":31\" /> SDS-controlled media companies have reportedly also served as a conduit for Hungarian financing of media in North Macedonia to prop up Orban's political allies there. Of the at least \u20ac4M in Hungarian moneys that were reportedly originally funneled into SDS-affiliated media between mid-2018 and early 2020, over \u20ac2.5M was then channeled to Macedonian news media entities favourable to the right-wing [[VMRO-DPMNE]] party.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://siol.net/novice/slovenija/madzarski-evri-za-medije-iz-krogov-sds-denar-tudi-v-makedonijo-518364|title=Mad\u017earski evri za medije iz krogov SDS, denar tudi v Makedonijo|website=siol.net|language=sl|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>\n\n== Parliamentary representation ==\n<timeline>\nImageSize  = width:500 height:200\nPlotArea   = width:400 height:170 left:50 bottom:20\nAlignBars  = justify\n\nDateFormat = yyyy\nPeriod     = from:0 till:32\nTimeAxis   = orientation:vertical\nScaleMajor = unit:year increment:5 start:0\n\nPlotData   =\n  bar:Seats color:claret width:30   mark:(line,white) align:left fontsize:S\n  bar:1990 color:yellow from:start till:6 text:6 \n  bar:1992 color:yellow from:start till:4 text:4 \n  bar:1996 color:yellow from:start till:16 text:16 \n  bar:2000 color:yellow from:start till:14 text:14 \n  bar:2004 color:yellow from:start till:29 text:29 \n  bar:2008 color:yellow from:start till:28 text:28 \n  bar:2011 color:yellow from:start till:26 text:26\n  bar:2014 color:yellow from:start till:21 text:21\n  bar:2018 color:yellow from:start till:25 text:25\n  </timeline>\n\n== Electoral performance ==\n{|class=wikitable style=\"text-align: right;\"\n|-\n!Election\n!Leader\n!Votes\n!%\n!Seats\n!+/\u2013\n!Position\n! style=\"width:140px;\"|Government\n|-\n![[1990 Slovenian parliamentary election|1990]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Jo\u017ee Pu\u010dnik]]\n|79,951\n|7.4\n|{{composition bar|6|80|hex=#FFD800}}\n|{{increase}} 6\n|{{increase}} 7th\n|{{yes|Coalition}}\n|-\n![[1992 Slovenian parliamentary election|1992]]\n|39,675\n|3.3\n|{{composition bar|4|90|hex=#FFD800}}\n|{{decrease}} 2\n|{{decrease}} 8th\n|{{yes|Coalition}}\n|-\n![[1996 Slovenian parliamentary election|1996]]\n| rowspan=\"9\" |[[Janez Jan\u0161a]]\n|172,470\n|16.3\n|{{composition bar|16|90|hex=#FFD800}}\n|{{increase}} 12\n|{{increase}} 3rd\n|{{no|Opposition}}\n|-\n![[2000 Slovenian parliamentary election|2000]]\n|170,228\n|15.8\n|{{composition bar|14|90|hex=#FFD800}}\n|{{decrease}} 2\n|{{increase}} 2nd\n|{{no|Opposition}}\n|-\n![[2004 Slovenian parliamentary election|2004]]\n|281,710\n|29.0\n|{{composition bar|29|90|hex=#FFD800}}\n|{{increase}} 15\n|{{increase}} 1st\n|{{yes|Coalition}}\n|-\n![[2008 Slovenian parliamentary election|2008]]\n|307,735\n|29.2\n|{{composition bar|28|90|hex=#FFD800}}\n|{{decrease}} 1\n|{{decrease}} 2nd\n|{{no|Opposition}}\n|-\n!rowspan=2|[[2011 Slovenian parliamentary election|2011]]\n|rowspan=2|288,719\n|rowspan=2|26.1\n|rowspan=2|{{composition bar|26|90|hex=#FFD800}}\n|rowspan=2|{{decrease}} 2\n|rowspan=2|{{steady}} 2nd\n|{{yes|Coalition <small>(2012\u20132013)</small>}}\n|-\n|{{no|Opposition <small>(2013\u20132014)</small>}}\n|-\n![[2014 Slovenian parliamentary election|2014]]\n|181,052\n|20.7\n|{{composition bar|21|90|hex=#FFD800}}\n|{{decrease}} 5\n|{{steady}} 2nd\n|{{no|Opposition}}\n|-\n!rowspan=2|[[2018 Slovenian parliamentary election|2018]]\n|rowspan=2|222,042\t\n|rowspan=2|24.9\n|rowspan=2|{{composition bar|25|90|hex=#FFD800}}\n|rowspan=2|{{increase}} 4\n|rowspan=2|{{increase}} 1st\n|{{no|Opposition <small>(2018\u20132020)</small>}}\n|-\n|{{yes|Coalition <small>(2020\u2013 )</small>}}\n|-\n|}\n\n== Party leaders ==\n'''Presidents of the Social Democratic Party and Slovenian Democratic Party'''\n* [[France Tom\u0161i\u010d]], 1989\u20131989\n* [[Jo\u017ee Pu\u010dnik]], 1989\u20131993\n* [[Janez Jan\u0161a]], 1993\u2013current\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n=== Tweets ===\n{{reflist|group=tweet}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.sds-online.org/ Official website]\n\n== Sources ==\n* {{cite book|first=Elisabeth|last=Bakke|chapter=Central and East European party systems since 1989|editor=[[Sabrina Ramet]]|title=Central and Southeast European Politics Since 1989|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2010|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oFXdiS25N78C&pg=PA244|ref=harv}}\n\n{{Slovenian political parties}}\n{{International Democrat Union}}\n{{European People's Party}}\n\n[[Category:1989 establishments in Slovenia]]\n[[Category:Conservative parties in Slovenia]]\n[[Category:Former member parties of the Socialist International]]\n[[Category:International Democrat Union member parties]]\n[[Category:Liberal conservative parties]]\n[[Category:Member parties of the European People's Party]]\n[[Category:Organizations that oppose same-sex marriage]]\n[[Category:National conservative parties]]\n[[Category:Organizations based in Ljubljana]]\n[[Category:Political parties established in 1989]]\n[[Category:Political parties in Slovenia]]\n[[Category:Right-wing populist parties]]\n[[Category:Right-wing populism in Slovenia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox political party\n| name = Slovenian Democrati